# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kathleen-dean-moore
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The first European settlers were originally from Connecticut.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Berea fell within Connecticut's Western Reserve and was surveyed and divided into townships and ranges by Gideon Granger, who served as postmaster general under President Thomas Jefferson.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Abram Hickox, a Revolutionary War veteran, bought the first plot in what is today Middleburg Heights and in 1808 traveled west from Connecticut to his new purchase.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Dissuaded by the swampy and heavily forested land, he decided to settle in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] He became successful as Cleveland's first full-time blacksmith.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] His plot of land was sold to his nephew, Jared Hickox, who came to the area with his wife Sarah and family in 1809.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] They followed an ancient Indian highway down through the forest from Cleveland and then, at what is now the corner of Bagley and Pearl roads, began to hack their way directly west.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] About two miles (3.2 km) in, they found Granger's plot markers and set up their homestead.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Today, this area is a strip mall on Bagley Road, just down the road from Berea.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] At the time Hickox discovered Granger's plot markers, the area was a swampy lowland, and as fate would have it, the Hickox's two grown sons died from typhoid fever shortly after the family's arrival.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The family farm was in dire straits, having been so severely depleted of male laborers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Love came to the rescue, however, and the area's spirits were lifted by its first marriage, that of Jared's daughter Amy Hickox to a recent arrival, Abijah Bagley.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Bagley ended up taking over the farm and managing it into a successful concern.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Today, Berea's largest street bears his name.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1827, educator John Baldwin moved to Middleburg Township, where he joined forces with James Gilruth and Henry Olcott Sheldon, Methodist circuit preachers, who wanted to form an ideal Christian community.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1836, they pledged to pool all their properties to create a Utopian "Community of United Christians." Members of the community vowed to avoid all luxuries and temptations that would prevent them from achieving the Methodist ideal of "sanctification" or perfect love of God.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1836, Baldwin and the others of the Utopian community tried to think of a name for their new town.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Nehemiah Brown proposed Tabor (perhaps from the biblical Mount Tabor), but Henry Sheldon suggested Berea, citing the biblical Berea in the Acts 17:10-11.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] They decided to let God decide the community's place name by flipping a coin, and the coin came up Berea.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Financial disputes led to the dissolution of the community and the departure of James Gilruth within a year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The Lyceum village concept never caught on in Berea due to the 1838 Public School Act, but the idea of an ideal community centered around a school continued even after the Berea Seminary closed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The failure of these two Utopian experiments left John Baldwin and Henry Sheldon in deep debt.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] However, Baldwin since 1838 had been making grindstones from sandstone in the creek bed of the Rocky River.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In the 1840s, Henry Sheldon began selling them via the Erie Canal in New York.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] This was the beginning of the Berea quarrying industry.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] After the Big Four Railroad was built from Cleveland to Cincinnati, Baldwin built a railroad to connect his quarries to the Big Four Depot.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1845, Baldwin convinced the North Ohio Conference of the Methodist Church to charter a new school, a new Utopian venture of sorts, because the new school, the Baldwin Institute, would provide education to all, regardless of sex, race, religious creed, or ability to pay.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1855, it was renamed Baldwin University.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] By the 1880s, the quarries had begun to intrude on the site of the university.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1891, the school broke ground for a new campus at Front Street and Bagley Road.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] New buildings were constructed and old buildings were moved.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1866, James Wallace purchased the site of the Lyceum village from the German Children's Home to become the German Wallace College Campus.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] In 1913, Baldwin University and German-Wallace College merged to become Baldwin–Wallace College, now Baldwin Wallace University.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Berea High School was the town's first high school, founded in 1882 and closed in 2020.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The current Berea–Midpark High School opened in 2020.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The geological stratum on which the city rests is the sedimentary formation Berea sandstone, a geological formation named after the city, which extends across Ohio, western Pennsylvania, and northern Kentucky.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] This comprises a sandstone laid down during the early Mississippian.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] After beginning of quarrying of the Berea sandstone in the 1830s, Baldwin initially shipped grindstones to Cleveland by ox carts, and later the quarries were connected to the railroad by a spur line.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Berea proclaims itself the "Grindstone Capital of the World".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The town's symbol is a grindstone, a tribute to the many grindstones that came out of its quarries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The quarries also provided sandstone that was extensively used as a construction material, in the form of Berea dimension stone.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Huge amounts of it came from Berea and were used architecturally in many important buildings.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The quarries closed in the late 1930s, when concrete came into wide use for construction.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Several lakes in the area are former quarry pits that have been allowed to fill with water, including Baldwin, Wallace, and Coe Lakes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Berea is located south/southwest of Brook Park and west of Middleburg Heights.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] According to the 2010 census, the city has a total area of 5.83 square miles (15.1 km2), of which 0.11 square miles (0.28 km2) (or 1.89%) is covered by water.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The east branch of the Rocky River runs through Berea, providing its water supply for most of the year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The Cleveland Metroparks' Rocky River and Mill Stream Run reservations run through the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] As of the 2020 census, Berea had a population of 18,545.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] 16.5% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.6% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] For every 100 females there were 93.0 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 90.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0% lived in rural areas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] There were 7,731 households in Berea, of which 22.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Of all households, 40.5% were married-couple households, 20.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] About 36.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] There were 8,174 housing units, of which 5.4% were vacant.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Among occupied housing units, 70.6% were owner-occupied and 29.4% were renter-occupied.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.1%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] As of the 2010 census, 19,093 people, 7,471 households, and 4,390 families resided in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The population density was 3,337.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,288.8/km2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The 7,958 housing units had an average density of 1,391.3 per square mile (537.2/km2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The racial makeup of the city was 88.8% White, 6.6% African American, 0.2% Native American, 1.5% Asian, 0.6% from other races, and 2.3% from two or more races.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Hispanics or Latinos of any race were 2.8% of the population.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Of the 7,471 households, 25.6% had children under 18 living with them, 43.7% were married couples living together, 11.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 41.2% were not families.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] About 33.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 or older.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 2.90.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The median age in the city was 37.1 years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The gender makeup of the city was 47.7% male and 52.3% female.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] As of the 2000 census, 18,970 people, 7,173 households, and 4,468 families lived in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The population density was 3,475.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,342.1/km2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The 7,449 housing units had an average density of 1,364.9 per square mile (527.0/km2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The racial makeup of the city was 91.48% White, 5.13% African American, 0.24% Native American, 0.90% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.61% from other races, and 1.61% from two or more races.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Hispanics or Latinos of any race were 1.59% of the population.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Of the 7,173 households, 34.9% had children under 18 living with them, 48.1% were married couples living together, 10.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.7% were not families.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] About 32.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.1% had someone living alone who was 65 or older.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The average household size was 2.35 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] For every 100 females, there were 90.4 males.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] For every 100 females 18 and over, there were 86.2 males.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The median income for a household in the city was $45,699 and for a family was $59,194.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Males had a median income of $39,769 versus $29,078 for females.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The per capita income for the city was $21,647.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] About 2.6% of families and 5.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 4.1% of those under 18 and 7.8% of those 65 or over.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Since 2023, Berea has been included in Ohio's 7th congressional district, represented by Republican Max Miller.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Baldwin Wallace College is the home of the Riemenschneider Bach Institute, a research institute devoted to J.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The first collegiate Bach festival in America was founded in 1932 by music educator Albert Riemenschneider and his wife Selma.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] As Riemenschneider conceived it, the festival would rotate Bach's four major works – the Mass in B minor, the St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Matthew Passion, and the Christmas Oratorio – every four years in sequence.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Since the inception of the festival, Baldwin Wallace students perform Bach works with faculty, as well as with international and local professionals.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The Berea City School District serves not just Berea, but also the neighboring cities of Brook Park and Middleburg Heights.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] Berea–Midpark High School is in Berea, and Berea-Midpark Middle School is in Middleburg Heights.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The high school and middle school partners with Polaris Career Center for Project Lead The Way classes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/berea-ohio] The three elementary schools are Grindstone (in Berea), Brook Park (in Brook Park), and Big Creek (in Middleburg Heights).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was founded in 1796 near the mouth of the Cuyahoga River as part of the Connecticut Western Reserve in modern-day Northeast Ohio by General Moses Cleaveland, after whom the city was named.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's location on the river and the lake shore allowed it to grow into a major commercial and industrial metropolis by the late 19th century, attracting large numbers of immigrants and migrants.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It was among the top 10 largest U.S. cities by population for much of the 20th century, a period that saw the development of the city's cultural institutions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy began to slow down as manufacturing declined and suburbanization occurred.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is a port city, connected to the Atlantic Ocean via the St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its economy relies on diverse sectors that include higher education, manufacturing, financial services, healthcare, and biomedicals.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city serves as the headquarters of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, as well as several major companies.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The GDP for Greater Cleveland was US$138.3 billion in 2022.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Combined with the Akron metropolitan area, the eight-county Cleveland–Akron metropolitan economy was $176 billion in 2022, the largest in Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Known as "The Forest City" among many other nicknames, Cleveland serves as the center of the Cleveland Metroparks nature reserve system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Cleveland Browns (football; NFL), the Cleveland Cavaliers (basketball; NBA), and the Cleveland Guardians (baseball; MLB).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was established on July 22, 1796, by surveyors of the Connecticut Land Company when they laid out Connecticut's Western Reserve into townships and a capital city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] They named the settlement "Cleaveland" after their leader, General Moses Cleaveland, a veteran of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleaveland oversaw the New England–style design of the plan for what would become the modern downtown area, centered on Public Square.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The town's name was often shortened to "Cleveland", including by Cleaveland's original surveyors.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A myth emerged that the spelling was altered by *The Cleveland Advertiser* to fit the name on the newspaper's masthead.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The first permanent European settler in Cleveland was Lorenzo Carter, who arrived in May 1797 and built a cabin on the banks of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The emerging community served as an important supply post for the U.S. during the Battle of Lake Erie in the War of 1812.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Largely through the efforts of the settlement's first lawyer, Alfred Kelley, the village of Cleveland was incorporated on December 23, 1814.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Despite the nearby swampy lowlands and harsh winters, the town's waterfront on Lake Erie was advantageous, giving it access to Great Lakes trade.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It grew rapidly after the 1832 completion of the Ohio and Erie Canal, which linked the Ohio River and the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean via the Erie Canal and Hudson River, and later via the Saint Lawrence Seaway.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The town's growth continued with added railroad links.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 1836, Cleveland, then only on the eastern banks of the Cuyahoga, was incorporated as a city; John W.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The neighboring municipality of Ohio City was a major rival to Cleveland until its annexation by the city in 1854.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A center of abolitionist activity, Cleveland (code-named "Station Hope") was a major stop on the Underground Railroad for escaped African American slaves en route to Canada.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city served as an important center for the Union during the American Civil War, creating a large manufacturing industry within the city and unprecedented growth.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its geographic location as a transportation hub on the Great Lakes contributed to its development as an industrial and commercial center.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Rockefeller founded Standard Oil in Cleveland; in 1885, he moved its headquarters to New York City.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's economic growth and industrial jobs attracted large waves of immigrants from Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, and Ireland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Urban growth was accompanied by labor unrest as workers demanded better wages and working conditions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Streetcar Strike of 1899 was one of the more violent instances of labor strife in the city during this period.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By 1910, Cleveland had become known as the "Sixth City" due to its status at the time as the sixth-largest U.S. city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its automotive companies included Peerless, Chandler, and Winton, maker of the first car driven across the U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Other manufacturing industries in Cleveland included steam cars produced by White and electric cars produced by Baker.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Euclid Avenue became known as "Millionaires' Row" for its prestige and elegance.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Major Progressive Era politicians were leaders in the city, including populist Mayor Tom L.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Johnson, who was responsible for the development of the Cleveland Mall Plan.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The era of the City Beautiful movement in Cleveland architecture saw wealthy patrons support the establishment of the city's major cultural institutions including the Cleveland Museum of Art, which opened in 1916, and the Cleveland Orchestra, established in 1918.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] African American migrants from the rural South arrived in Cleveland as part of the Great Migration for jobs, constitutional rights, and relief from racial discrimination.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By 1920 Cleveland had grown into a densely populated metropolis of 796,841, making it the fifth-largest city in the nation, with a foreign-born population of 30%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Radical labor movements gained popularity in the city, such as the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW), in response to the conditions of the largely immigrant and migrant workers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 1919, local socialist and IWW demonstrators clashed with anti-socialists in the May Day Riots, which occurred amid the First Red Scare and the strike wave that swept the U.S. that year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's population grew throughout the Roaring Twenties.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The decade saw the establishment of the city's Playhouse Square, and the rise of the risqué Short Vincent.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Bal-Masque balls of the avant-garde Kokoon Arts Club scandalized the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Jazz came to prominence in Cleveland during this period.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Prohibition was established in Ohio in May 1919 (although it was not well-enforced in Cleveland), became law with the Volstead Act in 1920, and was repealed nationally by Congress in 1933.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The ban on alcohol led to the rise of speakeasies throughout the city and organized crime gangs, such as the Mayfield Road Mob, who smuggled bootleg liquor across Lake Erie from Canada into Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 1929, Cleveland hosted the first of many National Air Races, and Amelia Earhart flew to the city from Santa Monica, California in the Women's Air Derby.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Van Sweringen brothers commenced construction of the Terminal Tower skyscraper in 1926 and oversaw its completion in 1927.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] When the building was dedicated as part of Cleveland Union Terminal in 1930, the city had a population of over 900,000.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's economy was greatly effected by the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and Great Depression.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A center of union activity, the city saw significant labor struggles in this period, including strikes by workers against Fisher Body in 1936 and against Republic Steel in 1937.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city was aided by major federal works projects sponsored by President Franklin D.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In commemoration of the centennial of Cleveland's incorporation as a city, the Great Lakes Exposition debuted in June 1936 at the city's North Coast Harbor, along the Lake Erie shore north of downtown.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Conceived by Cleveland's business leaders as a way to revitalize the city during the Depression, it drew four million visitors in its first season, and seven million by the end of its second and final season in September 1937.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] During World War II, Cleveland was a major hub of the U.S. war effort as the fifth largest manufacturing center in the nation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] During the war the city established the Cleveland Transit System, the predecessor to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland experienced an economic boom after the war and businesses declared the city to be the "best location in the nation".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The decade saw the rising popularity of the rock and roll music genre.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy slowed and residents sought new housing in the suburbs, reflecting national trends of suburban growth following federally subsidized highways.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Industrial restructuring, particularly in the steel and automotive industries, resulted in the loss of numerous jobs in Cleveland and the city suffered economically.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The burning of the Cuyahoga River in June 1969 brought national attention to the issue of industrial pollution in Cleveland and catalyzed the American environmental movement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Housing discrimination and redlining against African Americans led to racial unrest in Cleveland; the Hough riots erupted from July 18 to 24, 1966, and the Glenville Shootout took place on July 23, 1968.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In November 1967, Cleveland became the first major American city to elect an African American mayor, Carl B.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Stokes, who worked to restore the Cuyahoga River.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] During the 1970s, Cleveland was known as "Bomb City U.S.A." due to several bombings that shook the city, mostly due to organized crime rivalries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In December 1978, Cleveland became the first major American city since the Great Depression to enter a financial default on federal loans.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The national recession of the early 1980s eroded the city's traditional economic industries; Cleveland's unemployment rate of 13.8% was higher than the national average due to the closure of several steel production centers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city began an economic recovery in the 1980s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Although the city emerged from default in 1987, it suffered from the impact of the subprime mortgage crisis and the Great Recession.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By the 21st century, Cleveland had developed a more diversified economy and gained a national reputation as a center for healthcare and the arts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's downtown and several neighborhoods experienced significant population growth since 2010, while overall population decline has slowed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city has a total area of 82.47 square miles (213.6 km2), of which 77.70 square miles (201.2 km2) is land and 4.77 square miles (12.4 km2) is water.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The shore of Lake Erie is 569 feet (173 m) above sea level; the city lies on a series of irregular bluffs lying roughly parallel to the lake.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In Cleveland, these bluffs are cut principally by the Cuyahoga River, Big Creek, and Euclid Creek.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The land rises quickly from the lake shore elevation of 569 feet.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Public Square, less than one mile (1.6 km) inland, sits at an elevation of 650 feet (198 m), and Hopkins Airport, five miles (8.0 km) inland from the lake, is at an elevation of 791 feet (241 m).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland borders several inner-ring and streetcar suburbs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] To the west, it borders Lakewood, Rocky River, and Fairview Park, and to the east, it borders Shaker Heights, Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and East Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] To the southwest, it borders Linndale, Brooklyn, Parma, and Brook Park.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] To the south, the city borders Newburgh Heights, Cuyahoga Heights, and Brooklyn Heights and to the southeast, it borders Warrensville Heights, Maple Heights, and Garfield Heights.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] To the northeast, along the shore of Lake Erie, Cleveland borders Bratenahl and Euclid.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Many of the city's government and civic buildings, including City Hall, the Cuyahoga County Courthouse, the Cleveland Public Library, and Public Auditorium, are clustered around the open Cleveland Mall and share a common neoclassical architecture.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] They were built in the early 20th century as the result of the 1903 Group Plan.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] They constitute one of the most complete examples of City Beautiful design.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Completed in 1927 and dedicated in 1930 as part of the Cleveland Union Terminal complex, the Terminal Tower is a prototypical Beaux-Arts skyscraper.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It was the tallest building in North America outside New York City until 1964 and the tallest in the city until 1991.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Key Tower (the tallest building in Ohio) and 200 Public Square combine elements of Art Deco architecture with postmodern designs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Nicknamed Cleveland's "Crystal Palace", the five-story Cleveland Arcade (also known as the Old Arcade) was built in 1890 and renovated in 2001 as a Hyatt Regency Hotel.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Trust Company Building was completed in 1907 and renovated in 2015 as a downtown Heinen's supermarket.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's historic ecclesiastical architecture includes the Presbyterian Old Stone Church, the onion-domed St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Theodosius Russian Orthodox Cathedral, and the Roman Catholic Cathedral of St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] John the Evangelist along with several other ethnically inspired Catholic churches.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland City Planning Commission has designated 34 neighborhoods in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Centered on Public Square, Downtown Cleveland is the city's central business district, encompassing subdistricts such as the Nine-Twelve District, the Campus District, the Civic Center, East 4th Street, and Playhouse Square.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It also historically included the Short Vincent entertainment district.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Mixed-use areas, such as the Warehouse District and the Superior Arts District, are occupied by industrial and office buildings as well as restaurants, cafes, and bars.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The number of condominiums, lofts, and apartments has been on the increase since 2000 and especially 2010, reflecting downtown's growing population.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Clevelanders geographically define themselves by whether they live on the east or west side of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The East Side includes the neighborhoods of Buckeye–Shaker, Buckeye–Woodhill, Central, Collinwood (including Nottingham), Euclid–Green, Fairfax, Glenville, Goodrich–Kirtland Park (including Asiatown), Hough, Kinsman, Lee–Miles (including Lee–Harvard and Lee–Seville), Mount Pleasant, St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Clair–Superior, Union–Miles Park, and University Circle (including Little Italy).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cuyahoga Valley neighborhood (including Whiskey Island and the Flats) is situated between the East and West Sides, while Broadway–Slavic Village is sometimes referred to as the South Side.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Several neighborhoods have seen the return of the middle class that left the city for the suburbs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] These include Ohio City, Tremont, Detroit–Shoreway, and Edgewater on the West Side, and Collinwood, Hough, Fairfax, and Little Italy on the East Side.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The growth was spurred by attracting creative class members, which has facilitated new residential development and the transformation of old industrial buildings into loft spaces for artists.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland exhibits a humid continental (Köppen: *Dfa*) or humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) climate, depending on the isotherm used.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Due to its proximity to Lake Erie, Cleveland experiences milder temperatures than much of Ohio, with relatively cooler summers and warmer winters.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] East of the mouth of the Cuyahoga, the land elevation rises rapidly in the south.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Together with the prevailing winds off Lake Erie, this feature is the principal contributor to the lake-effect snow that is typical in Cleveland (especially on the city's East Side) from mid-November until the surface of the lake freezes, usually in late January or early February.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The lake effect causes a relative differential in geographical snowfall totals across the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] On the city's far West Side, the Hopkins neighborhood only reached 100 inches (254 cm) of snowfall in a season three times since record-keeping for snow began in 1893.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] By contrast, seasonal totals approaching or exceeding 100 inches (254 cm) are not uncommon as the city ascends into the Heights on the east, where the region known as the "Snow Belt" begins.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Extending from the city's East Side and its suburbs, the Snow Belt reaches up the Lake Erie shore as far as Buffalo.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The all-time record high in Cleveland of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on June 25, 1988, and the all-time record low of −20 °F (−29 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] On average, July is the warmest month with a mean temperature of 74.5 °F (23.6 °C), and January, with a mean temperature of 29.1 °F (−1.6 °C), is the coldest.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Normal yearly precipitation based on the 30-year average from 1991 to 2020 is 41.03 inches (1,042 mm).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The least precipitation occurs on the western side and directly along the lake, and the most occurs in the eastern suburbs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Parts of Geauga County to the east receive over 44 inches (1,100 mm) of liquid precipitation annually.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] With its extensive cleanup of its Lake Erie shore and the Cuyahoga River, Cleveland has been recognized by national media as an environmental success story and a national leader in environmental protection.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Since the city's industrialization, the Cuyahoga River had become so affected by industrial pollution that it "caught fire" a total of 13 times beginning in 1868.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It was the river fire of June 1969 that spurred the city to action under Mayor Carl B.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Stokes, and played a key role in the passage of the Clean Water Act in 1972 and the National Environmental Policy Act later that year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Since that time, the Cuyahoga has been extensively cleaned up through the efforts of the city and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In addition to continued efforts to improve freshwater and air quality, Cleveland is now exploring renewable energy.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's two main electrical utilities are FirstEnergy and Cleveland Public Power.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its climate action plan, updated in December 2018, has a 2050 target of 100% renewable power, along with reduction of greenhouse gases to 80% below the 2010 level.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In recent decades, Cleveland has been working to address the issue of harmful algal blooms on Lake Erie, fed primarily by agricultural runoff, which have presented new environmental challenges for the city and for northern Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has seen a population decline over the past century.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's population was 914,808 according to the 1950 Census.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] According to the 2020 census, there were 372,624 people and 170,549 households in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The population density was 4,901.51 inhabitants per square mile (1,892.5/km2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The median household income was $30,907 and the per capita income was $21,223.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] 32.7% of the population was living below the poverty line.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Of the city's population over the age of 25, 17.5% held a bachelor's degree or higher, and 80.8% had a high school diploma or equivalent.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] As of 2020, the racial and ethnic composition of the city was 47.5% African American, 32.1% non-Hispanic white, 13.1% Hispanic or Latino, 2.8% Asian, 0.2% Native American, and 3.8% from two or more races.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] 85.3% of Clevelanders age five and older spoke only English at home, while 14.7% spoke a language other than English, including Spanish, Arabic, Chinese, Hungarian, Albanian, and various Slavic languages (Russian, Polish, Serbian, Croatian, and Slovene).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's spoken accent is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English, similar to other Great Lakes cities, but distinctive from the rest of Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] , now serves an African American congregation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, Cleveland saw a massive influx of immigrants from Ireland, Italy, and the Austro-Hungarian, German, Russian, and Ottoman empires, most of whom were attracted by manufacturing jobs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The presence of Hungarians within Cleveland proper was, at one time, so great that the city boasted the highest concentration of Hungarians in the world outside of Budapest.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has a long-established Jewish community, historically centered on the East Side neighborhoods of Glenville and Kinsman, but now mostly concentrated in East Side suburbs such as Cleveland Heights and Beachwood, location of the Maltz Museum of Jewish Heritage.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the South.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Between 1910 and 1970, the black population of Cleveland, largely concentrated on the city's East Side, increased significantly as a result of the First and Second Great Migrations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's Latino community consists primarily of Puerto Ricans, as well as smaller numbers of immigrants from Mexico, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, South and Central America, and Spain.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's Asian community, centered on historical Asiatown, consists of Chinese, Koreans, Vietnamese, and other groups.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Additionally, the city and the county have significant communities of Albanians, Arabs (especially Lebanese, Syrians, and Palestinians), Armenians, French, Greeks, Iranians, Scots, Turks, and West Indians.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A 2020 analysis found Cleveland to be the most ethnically and racially diverse major city in Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The influx of immigrants in the 19th and early 20th centuries drastically transformed Cleveland's religious landscape.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] From a homogeneous settlement of New England Protestants, it evolved into a city with a diverse religious composition.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The predominant faith among Clevelanders today is Christianity, with Jewish, Muslim, Hindu, and Buddhist minorities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Within Cleveland, the neighborhoods with the highest foreign-born populations are Asiatown/Goodrich–Kirtland Park (32.7%), Clark–Fulton (26.7%), West Boulevard (18.5%), Brooklyn Centre (17.3%), Downtown (17.2%), University Circle (15.9%, with 20% in Little Italy), and Jefferson (14.3%).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Recent waves of immigration have brought new groups to Cleveland, including Ethiopians and South Asians, as well as immigrants from Russia and the former USSR, Southeast Europe (especially Albania), the Middle East, East Asia, and Latin America.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In the 2010s, the immigrant population of Cleveland and Cuyahoga County began to see significant growth.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A 2019 study found Cleveland to be the city with the shortest average processing time in the nation for immigrants to become U.S. citizens.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's annual One World Day in Rockefeller Park includes a naturalization ceremony of new immigrants.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's location on the Cuyahoga River and Lake Erie has been key to its growth as a major commercial center.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Steel and many other manufactured goods emerged as leading industries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city has since diversified its economy in addition to its manufacturing sector.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Established in 1914, the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland is one of 12 U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its downtown building, located on East 6th Street and Superior Avenue, was completed in 1923 by the Cleveland architectural firm Walker and Weeks.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The headquarters of the Federal Reserve System's Fourth District, the bank employs 1,000 people and maintains branch offices in Cincinnati and Pittsburgh.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland and Cuyahoga County are home to *Fortune 500* companies Cleveland-Cliffs, Progressive, Sherwin-Williams, Parker-Hannifin, KeyCorp, and Travel Centers of America.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] NASA maintains the Glenn Research Center in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Jones Day, one of the largest law firms in the U.S., was founded in Cleveland in 1893.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Healthcare plays a major role in Cleveland's economy.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's "Big Three" hospital systems are the Cleveland Clinic, University Hospitals, and MetroHealth.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Clinic is the largest private employer in the state of Ohio, with a workforce of over 55,000 as of 2022.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It carries the distinction of being one of the best hospital systems in the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The clinic is led by Croatian-born president and CEO Tomislav Mihaljevic and it is affiliated with Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] University Hospitals includes the University Hospitals Cleveland Medical Center and its Rainbow Babies & Children's Hospital.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cliff Megerian serves as that system's CEO.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] MetroHealth on the city's west side is led by president and CEO Christine Alexander-Rager.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Formerly known as City Hospital, it operates one of two Level I trauma centers in the city, and has various locations throughout Greater Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 2013, Cleveland's Global Center for Health Innovation opened with 235,000 square feet (21,800 m2) of display space for healthcare companies across the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] To take advantage of the proximity of universities and other medical centers in Cleveland, the Veterans Administration moved the region's VA hospital from suburban Brecksville to a new facility in University Circle.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's Playhouse Square is the second largest performing arts center in the U.S. behind New York City's Lincoln Center.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It includes the State, Palace, Allen, Hanna, and Ohio theaters.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The theaters host Broadway musicals, special concerts, speaking engagements, and other events throughout the year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Playhouse Square's resident performing arts companies include Cleveland Ballet, the Cleveland International Film Festival, the Cleveland Play House, Cleveland State University Department of Theatre and Dance, DANCECleveland, the Great Lakes Theater Festival, and the Tri-C Jazz Fest.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A city with strong traditions in theater and vaudeville, Cleveland has produced many renowned performers, most prominently comedian Bob Hope.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Outside Playhouse Square is Karamu House, the oldest African American theater in the nation, established in 1915.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] On the West Side, the Gordon Square Arts District in the Detroit–Shoreway neighborhood is the location of the Capitol Theatre, the Near West Theatre, and an Off-Off-Broadway playhouse, the Cleveland Public Theatre.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Dobama Theatre and the Beck Center for the Arts are based in Cleveland's streetcar suburbs of Cleveland Heights and Lakewood respectively.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Orchestra is widely considered one of the world's finest orchestras, and often referred to as the finest in the nation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] It is one of the "Big Five" major orchestras in the U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The orchestra plays at Severance Hall in University Circle during the winter and at Blossom Music Center in Cuyahoga Falls during the summer.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] One Playhouse Square, now the headquarters for Cleveland's public broadcasters, was initially used as the broadcast studios of WJW (AM), where disc jockey Alan Freed first popularized the term "rock and roll".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Beginning in the 1950s, Cleveland gained a strong reputation as a key breakout market for rock music.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Its popularity in the city was so great that Billy Bass, the program director at the WMMS radio station, referred to Cleveland as "The Rock and Roll Capital of the World".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Agora Theatre and Ballroom has served as a major venue for rock concerts in the city since the 1960s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] From 1974 through 1980, the city hosted the World Series of Rock at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Jazz and R&B have a long history in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Many major figures in jazz performed in the city, including Louis Armstrong, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, and Billie Holiday.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Legendary pianist Art Tatum regularly played in Cleveland clubs in the 1930s, and gypsy jazz guitarist Django Reinhardt gave his U.S. debut performance in Cleveland in 1946.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Prominent jazz artist Noble Sissle was a graduate of Cleveland Central High School, and Artie Shaw worked and performed in Cleveland early in his career.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Tri-C Jazz Fest has been held annually in Cleveland at Playhouse Square since 1980, and the Cleveland Jazz Orchestra was established in 1984.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city has a history of polka music being popular both past and present and is the location of the Polka Hall of Fame.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A subgenre called Cleveland-style polka, named after the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The music's popularity is due in part to the success of Frankie Yankovic, a Cleveland native who was considered "America's Polka King".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The first film shot in Cleveland was in 1897 by the company of Ohioan Thomas Edison.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Before Hollywood became the center for American cinema, filmmaker Samuel Brodsky and playwright Robert McLaughlin operated a film studio at the Andrews mansion on Euclid Avenue (now the WEWS-TV studio).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] There they produced major silent-era features, such as *Dangerous Toys* (1921), which are now considered lost.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Brodsky also directed the weekly *Plain Dealer Screen Magazine* that ran in theaters in Cleveland and Ohio from 1917 to 1924.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In addition, Cleveland hosted over a dozen sponsored film studios, including Cinécraft Productions, which still operates in Ohio City.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In the "talkie" era, Cleveland featured in several major studio films, such as Michael Curtiz's pre-Code classic *Goodbye Again* (1933) with Warren William and Joan Blondell.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Players from the 1948 Cleveland Indians appeared in *The Kid from Cleveland* (1949).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Billy Wilder's *The Fortune Cookie* (1966) was set and filmed in the city and marked the first onscreen pairing of Walter Matthau and Jack Lemmon.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Labor struggles in Cleveland were depicted in *Native Land* (1942), narrated by Paul Robeson, and in Norman Jewison's *F.I.S.T.* (1978) with Sylvester Stallone.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Clevelander Jim Jarmusch's *Stranger Than Paradise* (1984) – a deadpan comedy about two New Yorkers who travel to Florida by way of Cleveland – was a favorite of the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] *Major League* (1989) reflected the perennial struggles of the Cleveland Indians, while *American Splendor* (2003) reflected the life of Cleveland graphic novelist Harvey Pekar.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] *Kill the Irishman* (2011) depicted the 1970s turf war between Danny Greene and the Cleveland crime family.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has doubled for other locations in films.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The wedding and reception scenes in *The Deer Hunter* (1978), while set in suburban Pittsburgh, were shot in Cleveland's Tremont neighborhood.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] *A Christmas Story* (1983) was set in Indiana, but drew many external shots from Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The opening shots of *Air Force One* (1997) were filmed in and above Severance Hall, and *Judas and the Black Messiah* (2021) was filmed in Cleveland, although set in Chicago.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Downtown Cleveland doubled for Manhattan in *Spider-Man 3* (2007), *The Avengers* (2012), and *The Fate of the Furious* (2017), and for Metropolis in James Gunn's *Superman* (2025).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Future productions are handled by the Greater Cleveland Film Commission at the Leader Building on Superior Avenue.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In television, the city is the setting for the popular network sitcom *The Drew Carey Show*, starring Cleveland native Drew Carey.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] *Hot in Cleveland*, a comedy that aired on TV Land, premiered on June 16, 2010, and ran for six seasons until its finale on June 3, 2015.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] *Cleveland Hustles*, the CNBC reality show co-created by LeBron James, was filmed in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has a thriving literary and poetry community, with regular poetry readings at bookstores, coffee shops, and various other venues.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 1925, Russian Futurist poet Vladimir Mayakovsky came to Cleveland and gave a poetry recitation to the city's ethnic working class, as part of his trip to America.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland State University Poetry Center serves as an academic center for poetry in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Langston Hughes, preeminent poet of the Harlem Renaissance and child of an itinerant couple, lived in Cleveland as a teenager and attended Central High School in Cleveland in the 1910s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] At Central High, the young writer was taught by Helen Maria Chesnutt, daughter of Cleveland-born African American novelist Charles W.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Hughes authored some of his earliest poems, plays, and short stories in Cleveland and contributed to the school newspaper.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The African American avant-garde poet Russell Atkins lived in the city as well.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The American modernist poet Hart Crane was born in nearby Garrettsville, Ohio in 1899.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] His adolescence was divided between Cleveland and Akron before he moved to New York City in 1916.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland was the home of Joe Shuster and Jerry Siegel, who created the comic book character Superman in 1933.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Harlan Ellison, noted author of speculative fiction, was born in Cleveland in 1934.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] As a young man, he published a series of short stories appearing in the *Cleveland News*, and performed in a number of productions for the Cleveland Play House.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is the site of the Anisfield-Wolf Book Award, which recognizes books that have contributed to the understanding of racism and human diversity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Presented by the Cleveland Foundation, it remains the only American book prize focusing on works that address racism and diversity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Museum of Art is a major American art museum, with a collection that includes more than 60,000 works of art.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Museum of Contemporary Art Cleveland showcases established and emerging artists, particularly from the Cleveland area, through hosting and producing temporary exhibitions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Both museums offer free admission to visitors.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The two museums are part of Cleveland's University Circle, a 550-acre (2.2 km2) concentration of cultural, educational, and medical institutions located 5 miles (8.0 km) east of downtown.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In addition to the art museums, the neighborhood includes the Cleveland Botanical Garden, Case Western Reserve University, University Hospitals, Severance Hall, the Maltz Performing Arts Center, the Cleveland Museum of Natural History, and the Western Reserve Historical Society.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Also located at University Circle is the Cleveland Cinematheque at the Cleveland Institute of Art.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Pei-designed Rock and Roll Hall of Fame is located on Cleveland's Lake Erie waterfront at North Coast Harbor downtown.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Neighboring attractions include Cleveland Browns Stadium, the Great Lakes Science Center, the Steamship Mather Museum, the International Women's Air & Space Museum, and the USS *Cod*, a World War II submarine.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Scofield, the Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument at Public Square is Cleveland's major Civil War memorial and a major attraction in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Other city attractions include Grays Armory, the Cleveland Masonic Temple, and the Children's Museum of Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] A Cleveland holiday attraction, especially for fans of Jean Shepherd's *A Christmas Story*, is the Christmas Story House and Museum in Tremont.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland hosts the WinterLand holiday display lighting festival annually at Public Square.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland International Film Festival has been held in the city since 1977, and the Cleveland Silent Film Festival has been held since 2022.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland National Air Show, an indirect successor to the National Air Races, has been held at the city's Burke Lakefront Airport since 1964.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Great Lakes Burning River Fest, a two-night music and beer festival at Whiskey Island, has been sponsored by the Great Lakes Brewing Company since 2001.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Many ethnic festivals are held in Cleveland throughout the year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] These include the annual Feast of the Assumption in Little Italy, Russian Maslenitsa in Rockefeller Park, the Puerto Rican Parade and Cultural Festival in Clark–Fulton, the Cleveland Asian Festival in Asiatown, the Tremont Greek Fest, and the St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland also hosts annual Polish Dyngus Day and Slovene Kurentovanje celebrations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The city's annual Saint Patrick's Day parade brings hundreds of thousands to the streets of Downtown.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] The Cleveland Thyagaraja Festival held each spring at Cleveland State University is the largest Indian classical music and dance festival in the world outside of India.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Since 1946, the city has annually marked One World Day in the Cleveland Cultural Gardens in Rockefeller Park, celebrating all of its ethnic communities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland's mosaic of ethnic communities and their various culinary traditions have long played an important role in defining the city's cuisine.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Local mainstays include an abundance of Slavic, Hungarian, and Central-Eastern European contributions, such as kielbasa, stuffed cabbage, pierogies, goulash, and chicken paprikash.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Italian, German, Irish, and Jewish cuisines are also prominent in Cleveland, as are Lebanese, Greek, Chinese, Puerto Rican, Mexican, and numerous other ethnic cuisines.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Vendors at the West Side Market in Ohio City offer many ethnic foods for sale.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In addition, the city boasts a vibrant barbecue and soul food scene.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Slyman's Deli on Cleveland's near East Side is notable for its corned beef sandwich, with patrons including former U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Another celebrated sandwich, the Polish Boy, is a popular street food and Cleveland original frequently sold at downtown hot dog carts and stadium concession stands.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Brown stadium mustard is synonymous with Cleveland, especially Bertman Original Ballpark Mustard.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Another notable local food item with Depression-era roots is city chicken.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] With its blue-collar roots well intact, and plenty of Lake Erie perch and walleye available, the tradition of Friday night fish fries remains alive and thriving in Cleveland, particularly in ethnic parish-based settings, especially during the season of Lent.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Clambakes are likewise embedded into the city's culinary culture.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] For dessert, the Cleveland Cassata Cake is a unique treat invented in the local Italian community and served in Italian establishments throughout the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Another popular dessert, the locally crafted Russian Tea Biscuit, is common in many Jewish bakeries in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland is noted in the world of celebrity food culture.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Famous local figures include chef Michael Symon and food writer Michael Ruhlman, both of whom achieved local and national attention for their contributions to the culinary world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] In 2007, Symon helped gain the spotlight when he was named "The Next Iron Chef" on the Food Network.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] That same year, Ruhlman collaborated with Anthony Bourdain, to do an episode of his *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations* focusing on Cleveland's restaurant scene.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Ohio produces the fifth most beer in the U.S., with its largest brewery being Cleveland's Great Lakes Brewing Company.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland has had a long history of brewing, tied to many of its ethnic immigrants, and has reemerged as a regional leader in production.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Dozens of breweries exist within city limits, including large producers such as Market Garden Brewery.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Although breweries can be found throughout the city, the highest concentration is in the Ohio City neighborhood.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p01] Cleveland hosts expansions from other countries as well, including the Scottish BrewDog and German Hofbrauhaus.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's major professional sports teams are the Cleveland Guardians (Major League Baseball), the Cleveland Browns (National Football League), and the Cleveland Cavaliers (National Basketball Association).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Other professional teams include the Cleveland Monsters (American Hockey League), the Cleveland Charge (NBA G League), the Cleveland Crunch (Major League Indoor Soccer), Cleveland SC (National Premier Soccer League), and the Cleveland Fusion (Women's Football Alliance).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Local sporting venues include Progressive Field, Huntington Bank Field, Rocket Arena, the Wolstein Center, and Public Auditorium.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Guardians – known as the Indians from 1915 to 2021 – won the World Series in 1920 and 1948.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] They also won the American League pennant, making the World Series in the 1954, 1995, 1997, and 2016 seasons.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Between 1995 and 2001, the team sold out 455 consecutive games, a Major League Baseball record that stood until 2008.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Historically, the Browns have been among the most successful franchises in American football history, winning eight titles during a short period of time – 1946, 1947, 1948, 1949, 1950, 1954, 1955, and 1964.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Browns have never played in a Super Bowl, getting close five times by making it to the NFL/AFC Championship Game in 1968, 1969, 1986, 1987, and 1989.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Former owner Art Modell's relocation of the Browns after the 1995 season caused tremendous heartbreak and resentment among local fans.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] After a series of lawsuits, a compromise was reached between Modell, Cleveland mayor Michael R.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] White, and NFL and Commissioner Paul Tagliabue to bring back the Browns beginning in the 1999 season, retaining all team history.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In Cleveland's earlier football history, the Cleveland Bulldogs won the NFL Championship in 1924, and the Cleveland Rams won the NFL Championship in 1945 before relocating to Los Angeles.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cavaliers won the Eastern Conference in 2007, 2015, 2016, 2017 and 2018 but were defeated in the NBA Finals by the San Antonio Spurs and then by the Golden State Warriors, respectively.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cavs won the Conference again in 2016 and won their first NBA Championship coming back from a 3–1 deficit, finally defeating the Golden State Warriors.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Afterwards, over 1.3 million people attended a parade held in the Cavs' honor on June 22, 2016, in downtown Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Previously, the Cleveland Rosenblums dominated the original American Basketball League, and the Cleveland Pipers, owned by George Steinbrenner, won the American Basketball League championship in 1962.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Monsters of the American Hockey League won the 2016 Calder Cup.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] They were the first Cleveland AHL team to do so since the 1964 Barons.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Collegiately, NCAA Division I Cleveland State Vikings have 19 varsity sports, nationally known for their Cleveland State Vikings men's basketball team.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] NCAA Division III Case Western Reserve Spartans have 17 varsity sports, most known for their Case Western Reserve Spartans football team.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The headquarters of the Mid-American Conference (MAC) are in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The conference stages both its men's and women's basketball tournaments at Rocket Arena.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Marathon has been hosted annually since 1978, and a monument commemorating one of Cleveland's most prominent track and field athletes, Jesse Owens, stands at the city's Fort Huntington Park.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The second American Chess Congress, a predecessor to the U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Championship, was held in Cleveland in 1871, and won by George Henry Mackenzie.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Open Chess Championships took place in the city, and were won by Edward Lasker and Bobby Fischer, respectively.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In 2014, Cleveland hosted the ninth official Gay Games ceremony.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In July 2024, the city hosted the Pan American Masters Games.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Known locally as the "Emerald Necklace", the Olmsted-inspired Cleveland Metroparks encircle Cleveland and Cuyahoga County.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The city proper encompasses the Metroparks' Brookside and Lakefront Reservations, as well as significant parts of the Rocky River, Washington, and Euclid Creek Reservations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Lakefront Reservation, which provides public access to Lake Erie, consists of four parks: Edgewater Park, Whiskey Island–Wendy Park, East 55th Street Marina, and Gordon Park.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Three more parks fall under the jurisdiction of the Euclid Creek Reservation: Euclid Beach, Villa Angela, and Wildwood Marina.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Further south, bike and hiking trails in the Brecksville and Bedford Reservations, along with Garfield Park, provide access to trails in the Cuyahoga Valley National Park.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Also included in the Metroparks system is the Cleveland Metroparks Zoo, established in 1882.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Located in Big Creek Valley, the zoo has one of the largest collections of primates in North America.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition to the Metroparks, the Cleveland Public Parks District oversees the city's neighborhood parks, the largest of which is the historic Rockefeller Park.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The latter is notable for its late 19th century landmark bridges, the Rockefeller Park Greenhouse, and the Cleveland Cultural Gardens, which celebrate the city's ethnic diversity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Just outside of Rockefeller Park, the Cleveland Botanical Garden in University Circle, established in 1930, is the oldest civic garden center in the nation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition, the Greater Cleveland Aquarium, located in the historic FirstEnergy Powerhouse in the Flats, is the only independent, free-standing aquarium in the state of Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland operates on a mayor–council (strong mayor) form of government, in which the mayor is the chief executive and the city council serves as the legislative branch.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] City council members are elected from 15 wards to four-year terms.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] From 1924 to 1931, the city briefly experimented with a council–manager government under William R.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Morgan before returning to the mayor–council system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by Cleveland Municipal Court, the first municipal court in the state.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, based at the Carl B.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Chief Judge for the Northern District is Sara Elizabeth Lioi and the Clerk of Court is Sandy Opacich.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The office of the mayor has been held by Justin Bibb since 2022.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Previous mayors include progressive Democrat Tom L.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Johnson, World War I-era War Secretary and BakerHostetler founder Newton D.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Supreme Court Justice Harold Hitz Burton, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator Frank J.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Health, Education, and Welfare Secretary Anthony J.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Celebrezze, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator George Voinovich, former U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Congressman Dennis Kucinich, and Carl B.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Stokes, the first African American mayor of a major U.S. city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Jackson was the city's longest-serving mayor.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The President of Cleveland City Council is Blaine Griffin, the council Majority Leader is Jasmin Santana, and the Majority Whip is Charles Slife.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Patricia Britt serves as the Clerk of Council.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is a major stronghold for the Democratic Party in Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Although local elections are nonpartisan, Democrats still dominate every level of government.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Politically, Cleveland and several of its neighboring suburbs comprise Ohio's 11th congressional district.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The district is represented by Shontel Brown, one of five Democrats representing the state of Ohio in the U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Earlier, from the Civil War era to the 1940s, Cleveland had been dominated by the Republican Party, with the notable exceptions of the Johnson and Baker mayoral administrations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Businessman and Senator Mark Hanna was among Cleveland's most influential Republican figures, both locally and nationally.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Another nationally prominent Ohio Republican, former U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Garfield, was born in Cuyahoga County's Orange Township (today the Cleveland suburb of Moreland Hills).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Garfield Memorial in Cleveland's Lake View Cemetery.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has hosted three Republican national conventions, in 1924, 1936, and 2016.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Although the city has not hosted a national convention for the Democrats, it has hosted the 1864 Radical Democratic National Convention.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Additionally, Cleveland has hosted several national election debates, including the second 1980 U.S. presidential debate, the 2004 U.S. vice presidential debate, one 2008 Democratic primary debate, and the first 2020 U.S. presidential debate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Founded in 1912, the City Club of Cleveland provides a platform for national and local debates and discussions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Known as Cleveland's "Citadel of Free Speech", it is one of the oldest continuous independent free speech and debate forums in the country.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's Department of Public Safety includes the Division of Police, the Division of Fire, and the Division of Emergency Medical Service.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The city's director of Public Safety has been Wayne Drummond since 2024.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Like in other major American cities, crime in Cleveland is concentrated in areas with higher rates of poverty and lower access to jobs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In recent decades, the rate of crime in the city, although higher than the national average, experienced a significant decline, following a nationwide trend in falling crime rates.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] However, as in other major U.S. cities, crime in Cleveland saw an abrupt rise in 2020–21.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's law enforcement agency is the Cleveland Division of Police, established in 1866.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The division had roughly 1,100 sworn officers as of 2024, covering five police districts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The district system was introduced in the 1930s by Cleveland Public Safety Director Eliot Ness (of the Untouchables), who later ran for mayor of Cleveland in 1947.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition, the Cuyahoga County Sheriff's Office is based in Downtown Cleveland at the Justice Center Complex.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by the firefighters of the Cleveland Division of Fire, established in 1863.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The fire department operates out of 22 active fire stations throughout the city in five battalions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Each Battalion is commanded by a Battalion Chief, who reports to an on-duty Assistant Chief.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Division of Fire operates a fire apparatus fleet of twenty-two engine companies, eight ladder companies, three tower companies, two task force rescue squad companies, hazardous materials ("haz-mat") unit, and numerous other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The interim Chief of Department is Wayne Naida.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland EMS is operated by the city as its own municipal third-service EMS division.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland EMS is the primary provider of Advanced Life Support and ambulance transport within the city of Cleveland, while Cleveland Fire assists by providing fire response medical care.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Although a merger between the fire and EMS departments was proposed in the past, the idea was subsequently abandoned.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The EMS Commissioner is Orlando Wheeler.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland serves as headquarters to Coast Guard District 9 and is responsible for all U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Coast Guard operations on the five Great Lakes, the Saint Lawrence Seaway, and surrounding states accumulating 6,700 miles of shoreline and 1,500 miles of international shoreline with Canada.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Station Cleveland Harbor, located in North Coast Harbor, has a responsibility covering about 550 square miles of the federally navigable waters of Lake Erie, including the Cuyahoga and Rocky rivers, as well as a number of their tributaries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by the Cleveland Metropolitan School District.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It is the only K–12 district in Ohio under the direct control of the mayor, who appoints a school board.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Approximately 1 square mile (2.6 km2) of Cleveland's Buckeye–Shaker neighborhood is part of the Shaker Heights City School District.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The area, which has been a part of the Shaker school district since the 1920s, permits these Cleveland residents to pay the same school taxes as the Shaker residents, as well as vote in the Shaker school board elections.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] There are several private and parochial schools in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] These include Benedictine High School, Cleveland Central Catholic High School, Eleanor Gerson School, St.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is home to a number of colleges and universities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Most prominent among them is Case Western Reserve University (CWRU), a widely recognized research and teaching institution based in University Circle with several major graduate programs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] University Circle also contains the Cleveland Institute of Art and the Cleveland Institute of Music.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Downtown Cleveland is home to Cleveland State University, a public research university with eight constituent colleges, and the metropolitan campus of Cuyahoga Community College.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Ohio Technical College is also based in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's suburban universities and colleges include Baldwin Wallace University in Berea, John Carroll University in University Heights, and Ursuline College in Pepper Pike.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Established in 1869, the Cleveland Public Library is one of the largest public libraries in the nation with a collection of over 11 million physical materials in 2025.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It holds the Northeast Ohio Broadcast Archives, and the John G.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] White Special Collection, with the largest chess library in the world and a rare collection of folklore and books on the Middle East and Eurasia.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The library's main building was designed by Walker and Weeks and dedicated in 1925, under head librarian Linda Eastman, the first woman to lead a major library system in the U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Between 1904 and 1920, 15 libraries built with funds from Andrew Carnegie were opened in the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Known as the "People's University", the library presently maintains 27 branches.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It serves as the headquarters for the CLEVNET library consortium, which includes 47 public library systems in Northeast Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's primary daily newspaper is *The Plain Dealer* and its associated online publication, *Cleveland.com*.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Defunct major newspapers include the *Cleveland Press* and the *Cleveland News*.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Additional publications include *Cleveland Magazine*, a regional culture magazine published monthly; *Crain's Cleveland Business*, a weekly business newspaper; and *Cleveland Scene*, a free alternative weekly paper which absorbed its competitor, the *Cleveland Free Times*, in 2008.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The digital *Belt Magazine* was founded in Cleveland in 2013.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] *Time* magazine was published in Cleveland from 1925 to 1927.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Several ethnic publications are based in Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland-area television market is served by 11 full power stations, including WKYC (NBC), WEWS-TV (ABC), WJW (Fox), WDLI-TV (Bounce), WOIO (CBS), WVPX-TV (Ion), WVIZ (PBS), WUAB (MyNetworkTV), WRLM (TCT), WBNX-TV (CW), and WQHS-DT (Univision).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] As of 2021, the market, which includes the Akron and Canton areas, was the 19th-largest in the country, as measured by Nielsen Media Research.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is directly served by 29 full power AM and FM radio stations, 21 of which are licensed to the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] WMMS also serves as the FM flagship for the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians, WNCX is an FM flagship for the Cleveland Browns, and WJMO is the Spanish flagship for the Browns and Cavaliers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] News/talk stations include WHK, WTAM, and WERE.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] During the Golden Age of Radio, WHK was the first radio station to broadcast in Ohio, and one of the first in the country.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] WTAM is the AM flagship for both the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Sports stations include WKNR (ESPN), WARF (Fox/VSiN) and WKRK-FM (WW1), with WKNR and WKRK-FM serving as co-flagship stations for the Cleveland Browns, and WARF – though primarily an English language station – airing Spanish broadcasts of Cleveland Guardians home games.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Religious stations include WHKW, WCCR, and WCRF.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] As the regional NPR affiliate, WKSU serves all of Northeast Ohio (including both the Cleveland and Akron markets).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] College stations include WBWC (Baldwin Wallace), WJCU (John Carroll), and WRUW-FM (Case Western Reserve).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has a bus and rail mass transit system operated by the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority (RTA).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The rail portion is officially called the RTA Rapid Transit, but local residents refer to it as *The Rapid*.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It consists of three light rail lines, known as the Blue, Green, and Waterfront Lines, and a heavy rail line, the Red Line.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In 2008, RTA completed the HealthLine, a bus rapid transit line, for which naming rights were purchased by the Cleveland Clinic and University Hospitals.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It runs along Euclid Avenue from downtown through University Circle, ending at the Louis Stokes Station at Windermere in East Cleveland.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In 1968, Cleveland became the first city in the nation to have a direct rail transit connection linking the city's downtown to its major airport.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In 2021, Walk Score ranked Cleveland the 17th most walkable of the 50 largest cities in the U.S., with a Walk Score of 57, a Transit Score of 45, and a Bike Score of 55 (out of a maximum of 100).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's most walkable areas can be found in the Downtown, Ohio City, Detroit–Shoreway, University Circle, and Buckeye–Shaker neighborhoods.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Like other major cities, the urban density of Cleveland reduces the need for private vehicle ownership.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In 2016, 23.7% of Cleveland households lacked a car, while the national average was 8.7%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland averaged 1.19 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland's road system consists of numbered streets running roughly north–south, and named avenues, which run roughly east–west.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The numbered streets are designated "east" or "west", depending on where they lie in relation to Ontario Street, which bisects Public Square.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The two downtown avenues which span the Cuyahoga change names on the west side of the river.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Superior Avenue becomes Detroit Avenue on the West Side, and Carnegie Avenue becomes Lorain Avenue.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The bridges that make these connections are the Hope Memorial (Lorain–Carnegie) Bridge and the Veterans Memorial (Detroit–Superior) Bridge.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is served by three two-digit interstate highways – I-71, I-77, and I-90 – and by two three-digit interstates – I-480 and I-490.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Running due east–west through the West Side suburbs, I-90 turns northeast at the junction with I-490, and is known as the Cleveland Inner Belt.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Memorial Shoreway carries SR 2 along its length, and at varying points carries US 6, US 20 and I-90.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] At the junction with the Shoreway, I-90 makes a 90-degree turn in the area known as Dead Man's Curve, then continues northeast.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Jennings Freeway (SR 176) connects I-71 just south of I-90 to I-480.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] A third highway, the Berea Freeway (SR 237 in part), connects I-71 to the airport and forms part of the boundary between Brook Park and Cleveland's Hopkins neighborhood.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland is a major North American air market, serving 4.93 million people.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland Hopkins International Airport is the city's primary major airport and an international airport that serves the broader region.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Originally known as Cleveland Municipal Airport, it was the first municipally owned airport in the country.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland Hopkins is a significant regional air freight hub hosting FedEx Express, UPS Airlines, U.S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Postal Service, and major commercial freight carriers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition to Hopkins, Cleveland is served by Burke Lakefront Airport, on the north shore of downtown between Lake Erie and the Shoreway.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Burke is primarily a commuter and business airport.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Port of Cleveland, at the Cuyahoga River's mouth, is a major bulk freight and container terminal on Lake Erie, receiving much of the raw materials used by the region's manufacturing industries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Port of Cleveland is the only container port on the Great Lakes with bi-weekly container service between Cleveland and the Port of Antwerp in Belgium on a Dutch service called the Cleveland-Europe Express.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition to freight, the Port of Cleveland welcomes regional and international tourists who pass through the city on Great Lakes cruises.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland has a long history as a major railroad hub in North America.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Today, Amtrak provides service to Cleveland, via the *Capitol Limited* and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, which stop at Cleveland Lakefront Station.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Additionally, Cleveland hosts several inter-modal freight railroad terminals, for Norfolk Southern, CSX and several smaller companies.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] National intercity bus service is provided by Greyhound.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Akron Metro, Brunswick Transit Alternative, Laketran, Lorain County Transit, and Medina County Transit provide connecting bus service to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Geauga County Transit and Portage Area Regional Transportation Authority (PARTA) also offer connecting bus service in their neighboring areas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Cleveland maintains cultural, economic, and educational ties with 28 sister cities around the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] It concluded its first sister city partnership with Lima, Peru, in 1964.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In addition, Cleveland hosts the Consulate General of the Republic of Slovenia, which, until Slovene independence in 1991, served as an official consulate for Tito's Yugoslavia.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Clinic operates the Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi hospital, two outpatient clinics in Toronto, and a hospital campus in London.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] The Cleveland Council on World Affairs was established in 1923.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Historically, Cleveland industrialist Cyrus S.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] Rockefeller, played a significant role in promoting dialogue between the U.S. and the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/cleveland-p02] In October 1915 at Cleveland's Bohemian National Hall, Czech American and Slovak American representatives signed the Cleveland Agreement, calling for the formation of a joint Czech and Slovak state.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Natural forces cause some variability, but the persistent temperature increase shows the progressive influence of human activity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Present-day **climate change** includes both **global warming**—the ongoing increase in global average temperature—and its wider effects on Earth's climate system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change in a broader sense also includes previous long-term changes to Earth's climate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The modern-day rise in global temperatures is driven by human activities, especially fossil fuel (coal, oil and natural gas) burning since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use, deforestation, and some agricultural and industrial practices release greenhouse gases.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These gases absorb some of the heat that the Earth radiates after it warms from sunlight, warming the lower atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Earth's atmosphere now has roughly 50% more carbon dioxide, the main gas driving global warming, than it did at the end of the pre-industrial era, reaching levels not seen for millions of years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change has an increasingly large impact on the environment.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Heat waves and wildfires are becoming more common.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Amplified warming in the Arctic has contributed to thawing permafrost, retreat of glaciers and sea ice decline.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Higher temperatures are also causing more intense storms, droughts, and other weather extremes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Rapid environmental change in mountains, coral reefs, and the Arctic is forcing many species to relocate or become extinct.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Even if efforts to minimize future warming are successful, some effects will continue for centuries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These include ocean heating, ocean acidification and sea level rise.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens people with increased flooding, extreme heat, increased food and water scarcity, more disease, and economic loss.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Human migration and conflict can also be a result.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The World Health Organization calls climate change one of the biggest threats to global health in the 21st century.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Societies and ecosystems will experience more severe risks without action to limit warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Adapting to climate change through efforts like flood control measures or drought-resistant crops partially reduces climate change risks, although some limits to adaptation have already been reached.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Poorer communities are responsible for a small share of global emissions, yet have the least ability to adapt and are most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] , and worsening droughts compromising water supplies.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Many climate change impacts have been observed in the first decades of the 21st century, with 2024 the warmest on record at +1.60 °C (2.88 °F) since regular tracking began in 1850.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Additional warming will increase these impacts and can trigger tipping points, such as melting all of the Greenland ice sheet.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Under the 2015 Paris Agreement, nations collectively agreed to keep warming "well under 2 °C".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] However, with pledges made under the Agreement, global warming would still reach about 2.8 °C (5.0 °F) by the end of the century.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] There is widespread support for climate action worldwide, and most countries aim to stop emitting carbon dioxide.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuels can be phased out by ending their subsidies, conserving energy and switching to energy sources that do not produce significant carbon pollution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These energy sources include wind, solar, hydro, and nuclear power.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Cleanly generated electricity can replace fossil fuels for powering transportation, heating buildings, and running industrial processes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Carbon can also be removed from the atmosphere, for instance by increasing forest cover and farming with methods that store carbon in soil.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Before the 1980s, it was unclear whether the warming effect of increased greenhouse gases was stronger than the cooling effect of airborne particulates in air pollution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Scientists used the term *inadvertent climate modification* to refer to human impacts on the climate at this time.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In the 1980s, the terms *global warming* and *climate change* became more common, often being used interchangeably.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Scientifically, *global warming* refers only to increased global average surface temperature, while *climate change* describes both global warming and its effects on Earth's climate system, such as precipitation changes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Over the last few million years the climate cycled through ice ages.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] One of the hotter periods was the Last Interglacial, around 125,000 years ago, where temperatures were between 0.5 °C and 1.5 °C warmer than before the start of global warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This period saw sea levels 5 to 10 metres higher than today.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The most recent glacial maximum 20,000 years ago was some 5–7 °C colder.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This period has sea levels that were over 125 metres (410 ft) lower than today.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Temperatures stabilized in the current interglacial period beginning 11,700 years ago.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This period also saw the start of agriculture.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Historical patterns of warming and cooling, like the Medieval Warm Period and the Little Ice Age, did not occur at the same time across different regions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Temperatures may have reached as high as those of the late 20th century in a limited set of regions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate information for that period comes from climate proxies, such as trees and ice cores.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Around 1850 thermometer records began to provide global coverage.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Between the 18th century and 1970 there was little net warming, as the warming impact of greenhouse gas emissions was offset by cooling from sulfur dioxide emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Sulfur dioxide causes acid rain, but it also produces sulfate aerosols in the atmosphere, which reflect sunlight and cause global dimming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] After 1970, the increasing accumulation of greenhouse gases and controls on sulfur pollution led to a marked increase in temperature.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Ongoing changes in climate have had no precedent for several thousand years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Multiple datasets all show worldwide increases in surface temperature, at a rate of around 0.2 °C per decade.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Not every single year was warmer than the last: internal climate variability processes can make any year 0.2 °C warmer or colder than the average.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] From 1998 to 2013, negative phases of two such processes, Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) and Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) caused a short slower period of warming called the "global warming hiatus".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] After the "hiatus", the opposite occurred, with 2024 well above the recent average at more than +1.5 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This is why the temperature change is defined in terms of a 20-year average, which reduces the noise of hot and cold years and decadal climate patterns, and detects the long-term signal.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] A wide range of other observations reinforce the evidence of warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere is cooling, because greenhouse gases are trapping heat near the Earth's surface, and so less heat is radiating into space.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Warming reduces average snow cover and forces the retreat of glaciers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] At the same time, warming also causes greater evaporation from the oceans, leading to more atmospheric humidity, and more and heavier precipitation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Plants are flowering earlier in spring, and thousands of animal species have been permanently moving to cooler areas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Different regions of the world warm at different rates.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The pattern is independent of where greenhouse gases are emitted, because the gases persist long enough to diffuse across the planet.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Since the pre-industrial period, the average surface temperature over land regions has increased almost twice as fast as the global average surface temperature.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This is because oceans lose more heat by evaporation and oceans can store a lot of heat.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The thermal energy in the global climate system has grown with only brief pauses since at least 1970, and over 90% of this extra energy has been stored in the ocean.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The rest has heated the atmosphere, melted ice, and warmed the continents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere and the North Pole have warmed much faster than the South Pole and Southern Hemisphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere not only has much more land, but also more seasonal snow cover and sea ice.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] As these surfaces flip from reflecting a lot of light to being dark after the ice has melted, they start absorbing more heat.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Local black carbon deposits on snow and ice also contribute to Arctic warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Arctic surface temperatures are increasing between three and four times faster than in the rest of the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Melting of ice sheets near the poles weakens both the Atlantic and the Antarctic limb of thermohaline circulation, which further changes the distribution of heat and precipitation around the globe.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The World Meteorological Organization estimates there is almost a 50% chance of the five-year average global temperature exceeding +1.5 °C between 2024 and 2028.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The IPCC expects the 20-year average to exceed +1.5 °C in the early 2030s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report (2021) included projections that by 2100 global warming is very likely to reach 1.0–1.8 °C under a scenario with very low emissions of greenhouse gases, 2.1–3.5 °C under an intermediate emissions scenario, or 3.3–5.7 °C under a very high emissions scenario.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The warming will continue past 2100 in the intermediate and high emission scenarios, with future projections of global surface temperatures by year 2300 being similar to millions of years ago.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The remaining carbon budget for staying beneath certain temperature increases is determined by modelling the carbon cycle and climate sensitivity to greenhouse gases.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] According to UNEP, global warming can be kept below 2.0 °C with a 50% chance if emissions after 2023 do not exceed 900 gigatonnes of CO2.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This carbon budget corresponds to around 16 years of current emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The climate system experiences various cycles on its own which can last for years, decades or even centuries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For example, El Niño events cause short-term spikes in surface temperature while La Niña events cause short term cooling.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Their relative frequency can affect global temperature trends on a decadal timescale.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Other changes are caused by an imbalance of energy from external forcings.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Examples of these include changes in the concentrations of greenhouse gases, solar luminosity, volcanic eruptions, and variations in the Earth's orbit around the Sun.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] To determine the human contribution to climate change, unique "fingerprints" for all potential causes are developed and compared with both observed patterns and known internal climate variability.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For example, solar forcing—whose fingerprint involves warming the entire atmosphere—is ruled out because only the lower atmosphere has warmed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Atmospheric aerosols produce a smaller, cooling effect.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Other drivers, such as changes in albedo, are less impactful.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Greenhouse gases are transparent to sunlight, and thus allow it to pass through the atmosphere to heat the Earth's surface.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The Earth radiates it as heat, and greenhouse gases absorb a portion of it.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This absorption slows the rate at which heat escapes into space, trapping heat near the Earth's surface and warming it over time.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While water vapour (≈50%) and clouds (≈25%) are the biggest contributors to the greenhouse effect, they primarily change as a function of temperature and are therefore mostly considered to be feedbacks that change climate sensitivity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] On the other hand, concentrations of gases such as CO2 (≈20%), tropospheric ozone, CFCs and nitrous oxide are added or removed independently from temperature, and are therefore considered to be external forcings that change global temperatures.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Before the Industrial Revolution, naturally occurring amounts of greenhouse gases caused the air near the surface to be about 33 °C warmer than it would have been in their absence.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Human activity since the Industrial Revolution, mainly extracting and burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, and natural gas), has increased the amount of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In 2022, the concentrations of CO2 and methane had increased by about 50% and 164%, respectively, since 1750.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These CO2 levels are higher than they have been at any time during the last 14 million years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Concentrations of methane are far higher than they were over the last 800,000 years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Global human-caused greenhouse gas emissions in 2019 were equivalent to 59 billion tonnes of CO2.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Of these emissions, 75% was CO2, 18% was methane, 4% was nitrous oxide, and 2% was fluorinated gases.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] CO2 emissions primarily come from burning fossil fuels to provide energy for transport, manufacturing, heating, and electricity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Additional CO2 emissions come from deforestation and industrial processes, which include the CO2 released by the chemical reactions for making cement, steel, aluminium, and fertilizer.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Methane emissions come from livestock, manure, rice cultivation, landfills, wastewater, and coal mining, as well as oil and gas extraction.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Nitrous oxide emissions largely come from the microbial decomposition of fertilizer.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While methane only lasts in the atmosphere for an average of 12 years, CO2 lasts much longer.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The Earth's surface absorbs CO2 as part of the carbon cycle.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While plants on land and in the ocean absorb most excess emissions of CO2 every year, that CO2 is returned to the atmosphere when biological matter is digested, burns, or decays.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Land-surface carbon sink processes, such as carbon fixation in the soil and photosynthesis, remove about 29% of annual global CO2 emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The ocean has absorbed 20 to 30% of emitted CO2 over the last two decades.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] CO2 is only removed from the atmosphere for the long term when it is stored in the Earth's crust, which is a process that can take millions of years to complete.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Around 30% of Earth's land area is largely unusable for humans (glaciers, deserts, etc.), 26% is forests, 10% is shrubland and 34% is agricultural land.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Deforestation is the main land use change contributor to global warming, as the destroyed trees release CO2, and are not replaced by new trees, removing that carbon sink.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Between 2001 and 2018, 27% of deforestation was from permanent clearing to enable agricultural expansion for crops and livestock.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Another 24% has been lost to temporary clearing under the shifting cultivation agricultural systems.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] 26% was due to logging for wood and derived products, and wildfires have accounted for the remaining 23%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Some forests have not been fully cleared, but were already degraded by these impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Restoring these forests also recovers their potential as a carbon sink.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Local vegetation cover impacts how much of the sunlight gets reflected back into space (albedo), and how much heat is lost by evaporation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For instance, the change from a dark forest to grassland makes the surface lighter, causing it to reflect more sunlight.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Deforestation can also modify the release of chemical compounds that influence clouds, and can change the roughness of Earth’s surface in a way affecting wind speed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In tropic and temperate areas the net effect is to produce significant warming, and forest restoration can make local temperatures cooler.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] At latitudes closer to the poles, there is a cooling effect as forest is replaced by snow-covered (and more reflective) plains.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Globally, these increases in surface albedo have been the dominant direct influence on temperature from land use change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Thus, land use change to date is estimated to have a slight cooling effect.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Air pollution, in the form of aerosols, affects the climate on a large scale.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Aerosols scatter and absorb solar radiation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] From 1961 to 1990, a gradual reduction in the amount of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface was observed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This phenomenon is popularly known as *global dimming*, and is primarily attributed to sulfate aerosols produced by the combustion of fossil fuels with heavy sulfur concentrations like coal and bunker fuel.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Smaller contributions come from black carbon (from combustion of fossil fuels and biomass), and from dust.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Globally, aerosols have been declining since 1990 due to pollution controls, meaning that they no longer mask greenhouse gas warming as much.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Aerosols also have indirect effects on the Earth's energy budget.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Sulfate aerosols act as cloud condensation nuclei and lead to clouds that have more and smaller cloud droplets.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These clouds reflect solar radiation more efficiently than clouds with fewer and larger droplets.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] They also reduce the growth of raindrops, which makes clouds more reflective to incoming sunlight.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Indirect effects of aerosols are the largest uncertainty in radiative forcing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While aerosols typically limit global warming by reflecting sunlight, black carbon in soot that falls on snow or ice can contribute to global warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The resulting excess heat accelerates the melting of ice sheets and glaciers, which in turn contributes significantly to global sea-level rise.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Limiting new black carbon deposits in the Arctic could reduce global warming by 0.2 °C by 2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The effect of decreasing sulfur content of fuel oil for ships since 2020 is estimated to cause an additional 0.05 °C increase in global mean temperature by 2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] As the Sun is the Earth's primary energy source, changes in incoming sunlight directly affect the climate system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Solar irradiance has been measured directly by satellites, and indirect measurements are available from the early 1600s onwards.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Since 1880, there has been no upward trend in the amount of the Sun's energy reaching the Earth, in contrast to the warming of the lower atmosphere (the troposphere).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere (the stratosphere) would also be warming if the Sun was sending more energy to Earth, but instead, it has been cooling.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This is consistent with greenhouse gases preventing heat from leaving the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Explosive volcanic eruptions can release gases, dust and ash that partially block sunlight and reduce temperatures, or they can send water vapour into the atmosphere, which adds to greenhouse gases and increases temperatures.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These impacts on temperature only last for several years, because both water vapour and volcanic material have low persistence in the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Volcanic CO2 emissions are more persistent, but they are equivalent to less than 1% of current human-caused CO2 emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Volcanic activity still represents the single largest natural impact (forcing) on temperature in the industrial era.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Yet, like the other natural forcings, it has had negligible impacts on global temperature trends since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The climate system's response to an initial forcing is shaped by feedbacks, which either amplify or dampen the change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] *Self-reinforcing* or *positive* feedbacks increase the response, while *balancing* or *negative* feedbacks reduce it.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net cloud feedback.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The primary balancing mechanism is radiative cooling, as Earth's surface gives off more heat to space in response to rising temperature.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In addition to temperature feedbacks, there are feedbacks in the carbon cycle, such as the fertilizing effect of CO2 on plant growth.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Feedbacks are expected to trend in a positive direction as greenhouse gas emissions continue, raising climate sensitivity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These feedback processes alter the pace of global warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For instance, warmer air can hold more moisture in the form of water vapour, which is itself a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Warmer air can also make clouds higher and thinner, and therefore more insulating, increasing climate warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The reduction of snow cover and sea ice in the Arctic is another major feedback, this reduces the reflectivity of the Earth's surface in the region and accelerates Arctic warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This additional warming also contributes to permafrost thawing, which releases methane and CO2 into the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Around half of human-caused CO2 emissions have been absorbed by land plants and by the oceans.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This fraction is not static and if future CO2 emissions decrease, the Earth will be able to absorb up to around 70%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] If they increase substantially, it'll still absorb more carbon than now, but the overall fraction will decrease to below 40%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This is because climate change increases droughts and heat waves that eventually inhibit plant growth on land, and soils will release more carbon from dead plants when they are warmer.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The rate at which oceans absorb atmospheric carbon will be lowered as they become more acidic and experience changes in thermohaline circulation and phytoplankton distribution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Uncertainty over feedbacks, particularly cloud cover, is the major reason why different climate models project different magnitudes of warming for a given amount of emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] A climate model is a representation of the physical, chemical and biological processes that affect the climate system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Models include natural processes like changes in the Earth's orbit, historical changes in the Sun's activity, and volcanic forcing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Models are used to estimate the degree of warming future emissions will cause when accounting for the strength of climate feedbacks.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Models also predict the circulation of the oceans, the annual cycle of the seasons, and the flows of carbon between the land surface and the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The physical realism of models is tested by examining their ability to simulate current or past climates.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Past models have underestimated the rate of Arctic shrinkage and underestimated the rate of precipitation increase.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise since 1990 was underestimated in older models, but more recent models agree well with observations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The 2017 United States-published National Climate Assessment notes that "climate models may still be underestimating or missing relevant feedback processes".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Additionally, climate models may be unable to adequately predict short-term regional climatic shifts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] A subset of climate models add societal factors to a physical climate model.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These models simulate how population, economic growth, and energy use affect—and interact with—the physical climate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] With this information, these models can produce scenarios of future greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This is then used as input for physical climate models and carbon cycle models to predict how atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases might change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Depending on the socioeconomic scenario and the mitigation scenario, models produce atmospheric CO2 concentrations that range widely between 380 and 1400 ppm.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The environmental effects of climate change are broad and far-reaching, affecting oceans, ice, and weather.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Evidence for these effects comes from studying climate change in the past, from modelling, and from modern observations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Since the 1950s, droughts and heat waves have appeared simultaneously with increasing frequency.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Extremely wet or dry events within the monsoon period have increased in India and East Asia.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Monsoonal precipitation over the Northern Hemisphere has increased since 1980.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The rainfall rate and intensity of hurricanes and typhoons is likely increasing, and the geographic range likely expanding poleward in response to climate warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The frequency of tropical cyclones has not increased as a result of climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Global sea level is rising as a consequence of thermal expansion and the melting of glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise has increased over time, reaching 4.8 cm per decade between 2014 and 2023.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Over the 21st century, the IPCC projects 32–62 cm of sea level rise under a low emission scenario, 44–76 cm under an intermediate one and 65–101 cm under a very high emission scenario.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Marine ice sheet instability processes in Antarctica may add substantially to these values, including the possibility of a 2-meter sea level rise by 2100 under high emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change has led to decades of shrinking and thinning of the Arctic sea ice.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While ice-free summers are expected to be rare at 1.5 °C degrees of warming, they are set to occur once every three to ten years at a warming level of 2 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 concentrations cause more CO2 to dissolve in the oceans, which is making them more acidic.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Because oxygen is less soluble in warmer water, its concentrations in the ocean are decreasing, and dead zones are expanding.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Greater degrees of global warming increase the risk of passing through 'tipping points'—thresholds beyond which certain major impacts can no longer be avoided even if temperatures return to their previous state.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For instance, the Greenland ice sheet is already melting, but if global warming reaches levels between 1.7 °C and 2.3 °C, its melting will continue until it fully disappears.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] If the warming is later reduced to 1.5 °C or less, it will still lose a lot more ice than if the warming was never allowed to reach the threshold in the first place.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While the ice sheets would melt over millennia, other tipping points would occur faster and give societies less time to respond.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The collapse of major ocean currents like the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC), and irreversible damage to key ecosystems like the Amazon rainforest and coral reefs can unfold in a matter of decades.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The collapse of the AMOC would be a severe climate catastrophe, resulting in a cooling of the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The long-term effects of climate change on oceans include further ice melt, ocean warming, sea level rise, ocean acidification and ocean deoxygenation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The timescale of long-term impacts are centuries to millennia due to CO2's long atmospheric lifetime.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The result is an estimated total sea level rise of 2.3 metres per degree Celsius (4.2 ft/°F) after 2000 years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Oceanic CO2 uptake is slow enough that ocean acidification will also continue for hundreds to thousands of years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Deep oceans (below 2,000 metres (6,600 ft)) are also already committed to losing over 10% of their dissolved oxygen by the warming which occurred to date.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Further, the West Antarctic ice sheet appears committed to practically irreversible melting, which would increase the sea levels by at least 3.3 m (10 ft 10 in) over approximately 2000 years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Recent warming has driven many terrestrial and freshwater species poleward and towards higher altitudes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For instance, the range of hundreds of North American birds has shifted northward at an average rate of 1.5 km/year over the past 55 years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 levels and an extended growing season have resulted in global greening.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] However, heatwaves and drought have reduced ecosystem productivity in some regions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The future balance of these opposing effects is unclear.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] A related phenomenon driven by climate change is woody plant encroachment, affecting up to 500 million hectares globally.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change has contributed to the expansion of drier climate zones, such as the expansion of deserts in the subtropics.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The size and speed of global warming is making abrupt changes in ecosystems more likely.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Overall, it is expected that climate change will result in the extinction of many species.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The oceans have heated more slowly than the land, but plants and animals in the ocean have migrated towards the colder poles faster than species on land.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Just as on land, heat waves in the ocean occur more frequently due to climate change, harming a wide range of organisms such as corals, kelp, and seabirds.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Ocean acidification makes it harder for marine calcifying organisms such as mussels, barnacles and corals to produce shells and skeletons; and heatwaves have bleached coral reefs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Harmful algal blooms enhanced by climate change and eutrophication lower oxygen levels, disrupt food webs and cause great loss of marine life.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Coastal ecosystems are under particular stress.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Almost half of global wetlands have disappeared due to climate change and other human impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Plants have come under increased stress from damage by insects.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The effects of climate change are impacting humans everywhere in the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Impacts can be observed on all continents and ocean regions, with low-latitude, less developed areas facing the greatest risk.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Continued warming has potentially "severe, pervasive and irreversible impacts" for people and ecosystems.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The risks are unevenly distributed, but are generally greater for disadvantaged people in developing and developed countries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Scientists have warned about the irreversible harms it poses.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Extreme weather events affect public health, and food and water security.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Temperature extremes lead to increased illness and death.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change increases the intensity and frequency of extreme weather events.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] It can affect transmission of infectious diseases, such as dengue fever and malaria.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, 14.5 million more deaths are expected due to climate change by 2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] 30% of the global population currently live in areas where extreme heat and humidity are already associated with excess deaths.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] By 2100, 50% to 75% of the global population would live in such areas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While total crop yields have been increasing in the past 50 years due to agricultural improvements, climate change has already decreased the rate of yield growth.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Fisheries have been negatively affected in multiple regions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While agricultural productivity has been positively affected in some high latitude areas, mid- and low-latitude areas have been negatively affected.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change affects land suitability for many crops, with suitable areas for given crops usually moving to higher latitudes and altitudes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, an increase in drought in certain regions could cause 3.2 million deaths from malnutrition by 2050 and stunting in children.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] With 2 °C warming, global livestock headcounts could decline by 7–10% by 2050, as less animal feed will be available.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] If the emissions continue to increase for the rest of century, then over 9 million climate-related deaths would occur annually by 2100.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Economic damages due to climate change may be severe and there is a chance of disastrous consequences.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Severe impacts are expected in South-East Asia and sub-Saharan Africa, where most of the local inhabitants are dependent upon natural and agricultural resources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Heat stress can prevent outdoor labourers from working.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] If warming reaches 4 °C then labour capacity in those regions could be reduced by 30 to 50%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The World Bank estimates that between 2016 and 2030, climate change could drive over 120 million people into extreme poverty without adaptation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Inequalities based on wealth and social status have worsened due to climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Major difficulties in mitigating, adapting to, and recovering from climate shocks are faced by marginalized people who have less control over resources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Indigenous people, who are subsistent on their land and ecosystems, will face endangerment to their wellness and lifestyles due to climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] An expert elicitation concluded that the role of climate change in armed conflict has been small compared to factors such as socio-economic inequality and state capabilities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While women are not inherently more at risk from climate change and shocks, limits on women's resources and discriminatory gender norms constrain their adaptive capacity and resilience.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For example, women's work burdens, including hours worked in agriculture, tend to decline less than men's during climate shocks such as heat stress.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens the sports economy by disrupting seasons, damaging infrastructure and reducing fan engagement, with the most immediate risks seen in football, winter sports and outdoor events.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Low-lying islands and coastal communities are threatened by sea level rise, which makes urban flooding more common.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Sometimes, land is permanently lost to the sea.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This could lead to statelessness for people in island nations, such as the Maldives and Tuvalu.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In some regions, the rise in temperature and humidity may be too severe for humans to adapt to.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] With worst-case climate change, models project that areas almost one-third of humanity live in might become Sahara-like uninhabitable and extremely hot climates.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These factors can drive climate or environmental migration, within and between countries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] More people are expected to be displaced because of sea level rise, extreme weather and conflict from increased competition over natural resources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change may also increase vulnerability, leading to "trapped populations" who are not able to move due to a lack of resources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Climate change can be mitigated by reducing the rate at which greenhouse gases are emitted into the atmosphere, and by increasing the rate at which carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] To limit global warming to less than 2 °C global greenhouse gas emissions need to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This requires far-reaching, systemic changes on an unprecedented scale in energy, land, cities, transport, buildings, and industry.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The United Nations Environment Programme estimates that countries need to triple their pledges under the Paris Agreement within the next decade to limit global warming to 2 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] With pledges made under the Paris Agreement as of 2024, there would be a 66% chance that global warming is kept under 2.8 °C by the end of the century (range: 1.9–3.7 °C, depending on exact implementation and technological progress).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] When only considering current policies, this raises to 3.1 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Globally, limiting warming to 2 °C may result in higher economic benefits than economic costs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Although there is no single pathway to limit global warming to 2 °C, most scenarios and strategies see a major increase in the use of renewable energy in combination with increased energy efficiency measures to generate the needed greenhouse gas reductions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] To reduce pressures on ecosystems and enhance their carbon sequestration capabilities, changes would also be necessary in agriculture and forestry, such as preventing deforestation and restoring natural ecosystems by reforestation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Other approaches to mitigating climate change have a higher level of risk.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Scenarios that limit global warming to 1.5 °C typically project the large-scale use of carbon dioxide removal methods over the 21st century.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] There are concerns, though, about over-reliance on these technologies, and environmental impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Solar radiation modification (SRM) is a proposal for reducing global warming by reflecting some sunlight away from Earth and back into space.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Because it does not reduce greenhouse gas concentrations, it would not address ocean acidification and is not considered mitigation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] SRM should be considered only as a supplement to mitigation, not a replacement for it, due to risks such as rapid warming if it were abruptly stopped and not restarted.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The most-studied approach is stratospheric aerosol injection.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] SRM could reduce global warming and some of its impacts, though imperfectly.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] It poses environmental risks, such as changes to rainfall patterns, as well as political challenges, such as who would decide whether to use it.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Renewable energy is key to limiting climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For decades, fossil fuels have accounted for roughly 80% of the world's energy use.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The remaining share has been split between nuclear power and renewables (including hydropower, bioenergy, wind and solar power and geothermal energy).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use is expected to peak in absolute terms prior to 2030 and then to decline, with coal use experiencing the sharpest reductions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Renewables represented 86% of all new electricity generation installed in 2023.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Other forms of clean energy, such as nuclear and hydropower, currently have a larger share of the energy supply.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] However, their future growth forecasts appear limited in comparison.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] While solar panels and onshore wind are now among the cheapest forms of adding new power generation capacity in many locations, green energy policies are needed to achieve a rapid transition from fossil fuels to renewables.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] To achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, renewable energy would become the dominant form of electricity generation, rising to 85% or more by 2050 in some scenarios.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Investment in coal would be eliminated and coal use nearly phased out by 2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Electricity generated from renewable sources would also need to become the main energy source for heating and transport.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Transport can switch away from internal combustion engine vehicles and towards electric vehicles, public transit, and active transport (cycling and walking).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] For shipping and flying, low-carbon fuels would reduce emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Heating could be increasingly decarbonized with technologies like heat pumps.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] There are obstacles to the continued rapid growth of clean energy, including renewables.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Wind and solar produce energy intermittently and with seasonal variability.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Traditionally, hydro dams with reservoirs and fossil fuel power plants have been used when variable energy production is low.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Going forward, battery storage can be expanded, energy demand and supply can be matched, and long-distance transmission can smooth variability of renewable outputs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Bioenergy is often not carbon-neutral and may have negative consequences for food security.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The growth of nuclear power is constrained by controversy around radioactive waste, nuclear weapon proliferation, and accidents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Hydropower growth is limited by the fact that the best sites have been developed, and new projects are confronting increased social and environmental concerns.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Low-carbon energy improves human health by minimizing climate change as well as reducing air pollution deaths, which were estimated at 7 million annually in 2016.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Meeting the Paris Agreement goals that limit warming to a 2 °C increase could save about a million of those lives per year by 2050, whereas limiting global warming to 1.5 °C could save millions and simultaneously increase energy security and reduce poverty.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Improving air quality also has economic benefits which may be larger than mitigation costs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Reducing energy demand is another major aspect of reducing emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] If less energy is needed, there is more flexibility for clean energy development.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] It also makes it easier to manage the electricity grid, and minimizes carbon-intensive infrastructure development.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Major increases in energy efficiency investment will be required to achieve climate goals, comparable to the level of investment in renewable energy.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Several COVID-19 related changes in energy use patterns, energy efficiency investments, and funding have made forecasts for this decade more difficult and uncertain.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Strategies to reduce energy demand vary by sector.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In the transport sector, passengers and freight can switch to more efficient travel modes, such as buses and trains, or use electric vehicles.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Industrial strategies to reduce energy demand include improving heating systems and motors, designing less energy-intensive products, and increasing product lifetimes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In the building sector the focus is on better design of new buildings, and higher levels of energy efficiency in retrofitting.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The use of technologies like heat pumps can also increase building energy efficiency.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Agriculture and forestry face a triple challenge of limiting greenhouse gas emissions, preventing the further conversion of forests to agricultural land, and meeting increases in world food demand.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] A set of actions could reduce agriculture and forestry-based emissions by two-thirds from 2010 levels.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] These include reducing growth in demand for food and other agricultural products, increasing land productivity, protecting and restoring forests, and reducing greenhouse gas emissions from agricultural production.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] On the demand side, a key component of reducing emissions is shifting people towards plant-based diets.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Eliminating the production of livestock for meat and dairy would eliminate about three-quarters of all emissions from agriculture and other land use.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Livestock also occupy 37% of ice-free land area on Earth and consume feed from the 12% of land area used for crops, driving deforestation and land degradation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Steel and cement production are responsible for about 13% of industrial CO2 emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] In these industries, carbon-intensive materials such as coke and lime play an integral role in the production, so that reducing CO2 emissions requires research into alternative chemistries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Where energy production or CO2-intensive heavy industries continue to produce waste CO2, technology can sometimes be used to capture and store most of the gas instead of releasing it to the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] This technology, carbon capture and storage (CCS), could have a critical but limited role in reducing emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] It is relatively expensive and has been deployed only to an extent that removes around 0.1% of annual greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Natural carbon sinks can be enhanced to sequester significantly larger amounts of CO2 beyond naturally occurring levels.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Reforestation and afforestation (planting forests where there were none before) are among the most mature sequestration techniques, although the latter raises food security concerns.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Farmers can promote sequestration of carbon in soils through practices such as use of winter cover crops, reducing the intensity and frequency of tillage, and using compost and manure as soil amendments.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Forest and landscape restoration yields many benefits for the climate, including greenhouse gas emissions sequestration and reduction.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Restoration/recreation of coastal wetlands, prairie plots and seagrass meadows increases the uptake of carbon into organic matter.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] When carbon is sequestered in soils and in organic matter such as trees, there is a risk of the carbon being re-released into the atmosphere later through changes in land use, fire, or other changes in ecosystems.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] The use of bioenergy in conjunction with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) can result in net negative emissions as CO2 is drawn from the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] It remains highly uncertain whether carbon dioxide removal techniques will be able to play a large role in limiting warming to 1.5 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p01] Policy decisions that rely on carbon dioxide removal increase the risk of global warming rising beyond international goals.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Adaptation is "the process of adjustment to current or expected changes in climate and its effects".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Without additional mitigation, adaptation cannot avert the risk of "severe, widespread and irreversible" impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] More severe climate change requires more transformative adaptation, which can be prohibitively expensive.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The capacity and potential for humans to adapt is unevenly distributed across different regions and populations, and developing countries generally have less.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The first two decades of the 21st century saw an increase in adaptive capacity in most low- and middle-income countries with improved access to basic sanitation and electricity, but progress is slow.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Many countries have implemented adaptation policies.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] However, there is a considerable gap between necessary and available finance.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Adaptation to sea level rise consists of avoiding at-risk areas, learning to live with increased flooding, and building flood controls.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] If that fails, managed retreat may be needed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] There are economic barriers for tackling dangerous heat impact.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Avoiding strenuous work or having air conditioning is not possible for everybody.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In agriculture, adaptation options include a switch to more sustainable diets, diversification, erosion control, and genetic improvements for increased tolerance to a changing climate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Insurance allows for risk-sharing, but is often difficult to get for people on lower incomes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Education, migration and early warning systems can reduce climate vulnerability.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Planting mangroves or encouraging other coastal vegetation can buffer storms.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Ecosystems adapt to climate change, a process that can be supported by human intervention.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] By increasing connectivity between ecosystems, species can migrate to more favourable climate conditions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Species can also be introduced to areas acquiring a favourable climate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Protection and restoration of natural and semi-natural areas helps build resilience, making it easier for ecosystems to adapt.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Many of the actions that promote adaptation in ecosystems, also help humans adapt via ecosystem-based adaptation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] For instance, restoration of natural fire regimes makes catastrophic fires less likely, and reduces human exposure.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Giving rivers more space allows for more water storage in the natural system, reducing flood risk.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Restored forest acts as a carbon sink, but planting trees in unsuitable regions can exacerbate climate impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] There are synergies but also trade-offs between adaptation and mitigation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] An example for synergy is increased food productivity, which has large benefits for both adaptation and mitigation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] An example of a trade-off is that increased use of air conditioning allows people to better cope with heat, but increases energy demand.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Another trade-off example is that more compact urban development may reduce emissions from transport and construction, but may also increase the urban heat island effect, exposing people to heat-related health risks.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] ranks countries by greenhouse gas emissions (40% of score), renewable energy (20%), energy use (20%), and climate policy (20%).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Countries that are most vulnerable to climate change have typically been responsible for a small share of global emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] This raises questions about justice and fairness.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Limiting global warming makes it much easier to achieve the UN's Sustainable Development Goals, such as eradicating poverty and reducing inequalities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The connection is recognized in Sustainable Development Goal 13 which is to "take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The goals on food, clean water and ecosystem protection have synergies with climate mitigation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The geopolitics of climate change is complex.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] It has often been framed as a free-rider problem, in which all countries benefit from mitigation done by other countries, but individual countries would lose from switching to a low-carbon economy themselves.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Sometimes mitigation also has localized benefits though.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] For instance, the benefits of a coal phase-out to public health and local environments exceed the costs in almost all regions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Furthermore, net importers of fossil fuels win economically from switching to clean energy, causing net exporters to face stranded assets: fossil fuels they cannot sell.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] A wide range of policies, regulations, and laws are being used to reduce emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, carbon pricing covers about 20% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Carbon can be priced with carbon taxes and emissions trading systems.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Direct global fossil fuel subsidies reached $319 billion in 2017, and $5.2 trillion when indirect costs such as air pollution are priced in.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Ending these can cause a 28% reduction in global carbon emissions and a 46% reduction in air pollution deaths.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Money saved on fossil subsidies could be used to support the transition to clean energy instead.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] More direct methods to reduce greenhouse gases include vehicle efficiency standards, renewable fuel standards, and air pollution regulations on heavy industry.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Several countries require utilities to increase the share of renewables in power production.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] An Open Coalition on Compliance Carbon Markets with the aim of creating a global cap and trade system was established at COP30 (2025).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] According to some calculations it can increase emissions reduction seven-fold over current policies, deliver $200 billion per year for clean-energy and social programs and even close the gap between current emissions trajectory and the goals of the Paris agreement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Policy designed through the lens of climate justice tries to address human rights issues and social inequality.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] According to proponents of climate justice, the costs of climate adaptation should be paid by those most responsible for climate change, while the beneficiaries of payments should be those suffering impacts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] One way this can be addressed in practice is to have wealthy nations pay poorer countries to adapt.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Oxfam found that in 2023 the wealthiest 10% of people were responsible for 50% of global emissions, while the bottom 50% were responsible for just 8%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Production of emissions is another way to look at responsibility: under that approach, the top 21 fossil fuel companies would owe cumulative climate reparations of $5.4 trillion over the period 2025–2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] To achieve a just transition, people working in the fossil fuel sector would also need other jobs, and their communities would need investments.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Nearly all countries in the world are parties to the 1994 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The goal of the UNFCCC is to prevent dangerous human interference with the climate system.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As stated in the convention, this requires that greenhouse gas concentrations are stabilized in the atmosphere at a level where ecosystems can adapt naturally to climate change, food production is not threatened, and economic development can be sustained.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The UNFCCC does not itself restrict emissions but rather provides a framework for protocols that do.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Global emissions have risen since the UNFCCC was signed.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Its yearly conferences are the stage of global negotiations.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The 1997 Kyoto Protocol extended the UNFCCC and included legally binding commitments for most developed countries to limit their emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] During the negotiations, the G77 (representing developing countries) pushed for a mandate requiring developed countries to "[take] the lead" in reducing their emissions, since developed countries contributed most to the accumulation of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Per-capita emissions were also still relatively low in developing countries and developing countries would need to emit more to meet their development needs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The 2009 Copenhagen Accord has been widely portrayed as disappointing because of its low goals, and was rejected by poorer nations including the G77.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Associated parties aimed to limit the global temperature rise to below 2 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The accord set the goal of sending $100 billion per year to developing countries for mitigation and adaptation by 2020, and proposed the founding of the Green Climate Fund.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As of 2020, only $83.3 billion were delivered.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Only in 2023 the target is expected to be achieved.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In 2015 all UN countries negotiated the Paris Agreement, which aims to keep global warming well below 2.0 °C and contains an aspirational goal of keeping warming under 1.5 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The agreement replaced the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Unlike Kyoto, no binding emission targets were set in the Paris Agreement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Instead, a set of procedures was made binding.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Countries have to regularly set ever more ambitious goals and reevaluate these goals every five years.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The Paris Agreement restated that developing countries must be financially supported.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As of March 2025, 194 states and the European Union have acceded to or ratified the agreement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The 1987 Montreal Protocol, an international agreement to phase out production of ozone-depleting gases, has had benefits for climate change mitigation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Several ozone-depleting gases like chlorofluorocarbons are powerful greenhouse gases, so banning their production and usage may have avoided a temperature rise of 0.5 °C–1.0 °C, as well as additional warming by preventing damage to vegetation from ultraviolet radiation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] It is estimated that the agreement has been more effective at curbing greenhouse gas emissions than the Kyoto Protocol specifically designed to do so.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The most recent amendment to the Montreal Protocol, the 2016 Kigali Amendment, committed to reducing the emissions of hydrofluorocarbons, which served as a replacement for banned ozone-depleting gases and are also potent greenhouse gases.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Should countries comply with the amendment, a warming of 0.3 °C–0.5 °C is estimated to be avoided.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In 2019, the United Kingdom parliament became the first national government to declare a climate emergency.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Other countries and jurisdictions followed suit.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] That same year, the European Parliament declared a "climate and environmental emergency".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The European Commission presented its European Green Deal with the goal of making the EU carbon-neutral by 2050.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains guidelines for the car industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Major countries in Asia have made similar pledges: South Korea and Japan have committed to become carbon-neutral by 2050, and China by 2060.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] While India has strong incentives for renewables, it also plans a significant expansion of coal in the country.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Vietnam is among very few coal-dependent, fast-developing countries that pledged to phase out unabated coal power by the 2040s or as soon as possible thereafter.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Public debate about climate change has been strongly affected by climate change denial and misinformation, which first emerged in the United States and has since spread to other countries, particularly Canada and Australia.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] It originated from fossil fuel companies, industry groups, conservative think tanks, and contrarian scientists.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Like the tobacco industry, the main strategy of these groups has been to manufacture doubt about climate-change related scientific data and results.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] People who hold unwarranted doubt about climate change are sometimes called climate change "skeptics", although "contrarians" or "deniers" are more appropriate terms.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] There are different variants of climate denial: some deny that warming takes place at all, some acknowledge warming but attribute it to natural influences, and some minimize the negative impacts of climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Manufacturing uncertainty about the science later developed into a manufactured controversy: creating the belief that there is significant uncertainty about climate change within the scientific community to delay policy changes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Strategies to promote these ideas include criticism of scientific institutions, and questioning the motives of individual scientists.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] An echo chamber of climate-denying blogs and media has further fomented misunderstanding of climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Climate change came to international public attention in the late 1980s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Due to media coverage in the early 1990s, people often confused climate change with other environmental issues like ozone depletion.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In popular culture, the climate fiction movie *The Day After Tomorrow* (2004) and the Al Gore documentary *An Inconvenient Truth* (2006) focused on climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Significant regional, gender, age and political differences exist in both public concern for, and understanding of, climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] More highly educated people, and in some countries, women and younger people, were more likely to see climate change as a serious threat.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] College biology textbooks from the 2010s featured less content on climate change compared to those from the preceding decade, with decreasing emphasis on solutions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Partisan gaps also exist in many countries, and countries with high CO2 emissions tend to be less concerned.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Views on causes of climate change vary widely between countries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Media coverage linked to protests has had impacts on public sentiment as well as on which aspects of climate change are focused upon.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Higher levels of worry are associated with stronger public support for policies that address climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Concern has increased over time, and in 2021 a majority of citizens in 30 countries expressed a high level of worry about climate change, or view it as a global emergency.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] A 2024 survey across 125 countries found that 89% of the global population demanded intensified political action, but systematically underestimated other peoples' willingness to act.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Climate protests demand that political leaders take action to prevent climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] They can take the form of public demonstrations, fossil fuel divestment, lawsuits and other activities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Prominent demonstrations include the School Strike for Climate.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In this initiative, young people across the globe have been protesting since 2018 by skipping school on Fridays, inspired by Swedish activist and then-teenager Greta Thunberg.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Mass civil disobedience actions by groups like Extinction Rebellion have protested by disrupting roads and public transport.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Litigation is increasingly used as a tool to strengthen climate action from public institutions and companies.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Activists also initiate lawsuits which target governments and demand that they take ambitious action or enforce existing laws on climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Lawsuits against fossil-fuel companies generally seek compensation for loss and damage.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] On 23 July 2025, the UN's International Court of Justice issued its advisory opinion, saying explicitly that states must act to stop climate change, and if they fail to accomplish that duty, other states can sue them.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] This obligation includes implementing their commitments in international agreements they are parties to, such as the 2015 Paris Climate Accord.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Scientists in the 19th century such as Alexander von Humboldt began to foresee the effects of climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In the 1820s, Joseph Fourier proposed the greenhouse effect to explain why Earth's temperature was higher than the Sun's energy alone could explain.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Earth's atmosphere is transparent to sunlight, so sunlight reaches the surface where it is converted to heat.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] However, the atmosphere is not transparent to heat radiating from the surface, and captures some of that heat, which in turn warms the planet.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In 1856 Eunice Newton Foote demonstrated that the warming effect of the Sun is greater for air with water vapour than for dry air, and that the effect is even greater with carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In "Circumstances Affecting the Heat of the Sun's Rays" she concluded that "[a]n atmosphere of that gas would give to our earth a high temperature".
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Starting in 1859, John Tyndall established that nitrogen and oxygen—together totalling 99% of dry air—are transparent to radiated heat.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] However, water vapour and gases such as methane and carbon dioxide absorb radiated heat and re-radiate that heat into the atmosphere.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Tyndall proposed that changes in the concentrations of these gases may have caused climatic changes in the past, including ice ages.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Svante Arrhenius noted that water vapour in air continuously varied, but the CO2 concentration in air was influenced by long-term geological processes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Warming from increased CO2 levels would increase the amount of water vapour, amplifying warming in a positive feedback loop.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In 1896, he published the first climate model of its kind, projecting that halving CO2 levels could have produced a drop in temperature initiating an ice age.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Arrhenius calculated the temperature increase expected from doubling CO2 to be around 5–6 °C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Other scientists were initially sceptical and believed that the greenhouse effect was saturated so that adding more CO2 would make no difference, and that the climate would be self-regulating.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Beginning in 1938, Guy Stewart Callendar published evidence that climate was warming and CO2 levels were rising, but his calculations met the same objections.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] In the 1950s, Gilbert Plass created a detailed computer model that included different atmospheric layers and the infrared spectrum.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] This model predicted that increasing CO2 levels would cause warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Around the same time, Hans Suess found evidence that CO2 levels had been rising, and Roger Revelle showed that the oceans would not absorb the increase.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The two scientists subsequently helped Charles Keeling to begin a record of continued increase—the "Keeling Curve"—which was part of continued scientific investigation through the 1960s into possible human causation of global warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Studies such as the National Research Council's 1979 Charney Report supported the accuracy of climate models that forecast significant warming.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Human causation of observed global warming and dangers of unmitigated warming were publicly presented in James Hansen's 1988 testimony before a US Senate committee.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), set up in 1988 to provide formal advice to the world's governments, spurred interdisciplinary research.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As part of the IPCC reports, scientists assess the scientific discussion that takes place in peer-reviewed journal articles.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] There is a nearly unanimous scientific consensus that the climate is warming and that this is caused by human activities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] No scientific body of national or international standing disagrees with this view.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, agreement in recent literature reached over 99%.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] The 2021 IPCC Assessment Report stated that it is "unequivocal" that climate change is caused by humans.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Consensus has further developed that action should be taken to protect people against the impacts of climate change.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] National science academies have called on world leaders to cut global emissions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Extreme event attribution (EEA), also known as attribution science, was developed in the early decades of the 21st century.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] EEA uses climate models to identify and quantify the role that human-caused climate change plays in the frequency, intensity, duration, and impacts of specific individual extreme weather events.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Greater computing power in the 2000s and conceptual breakthroughs in the early to mid 2010s enabled attribution science to detect the effects of climate change on some events with high confidence.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/climate-change-p02] Scientists use attribution methods and climate simulations that have already been peer reviewed, allowing "rapid attribution studies" to be published within a "news cycle" time frame after weather events.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The **College of Wooster** is a private liberal arts college in Wooster, Ohio, United States.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Founded in 1866 by the Presbyterian Church as the University of Wooster, it has been officially non-sectarian since 1969.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] From its creation, the college has been a co-educational institution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] It enrolls about 1,900 students and is a member of the Five Colleges of Ohio, Great Lakes Colleges Association, and Association of Presbyterian Colleges and Universities.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Founded as the **University of Wooster** in 1866 by the Presbyterian Synod of Ohio, the institution opened its doors in 1870 with a faculty of five and a student body of thirty men and four women.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Ephraim Quinby, a Wooster citizen, donated the first 20 acres (8.1 ha), a large oak grove situated on a hilltop overlooking the town.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] After being founded with the intent to make Wooster open to everyone, the university's first Ph.D. was granted to a woman, Annie B.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The first black student, Clarence Allen, began his studies later in the same decade.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The university gradually began to define itself as a liberal arts institution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] In 1915, after a bitter dispute between the faculty and the trustees, the institution was renamed The College of Wooster reflecting a dedication to the education of undergraduate students in the liberal arts.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college developed under the presidency of Charles F.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] During the Fundamentalist–Modernist Controversy in the 1920s, prominent Presbyterian layman and former United States Secretary of State William Jennings Bryan attacked the college for its teaching of evolution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The subject had been taught at the college for several decades and defended by president Wishart.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Bryan called for the general assembly of the church to cut off funding to the college.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] In 1923, Wishart defeated Bryan for the position of Moderator of the General Assembly, largely on the evolution issue, and the college continued to teach evolution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Lowry, who served from 1944 until his death in 1967.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] On November 10, 2015, the college named Sarah Bolton as its twelfth president and first female president.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Bolton left the college at the end of the 2021–2022 academic year to assume the presidency of Whitman College.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] McCall was inaugurated on October 28, 2023.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster's school colors are black and old gold and its mascot is the 'Fighting Scot'.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Scottish culture became an important part of the school's heritage; today, the football games feature a Scottish pipe band with Highland dancers in addition to a traditional marching band, with all three groups clad in the MacLeod tartan.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college offers the "Scottish Arts Scholarship" for students who perform as pipers, drummers, or Scottish dancers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster has had fifteen presidents from 1870 to 2024, including interim presidents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The College of Wooster Board of Trustees named Anne E.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] McCall to be the 13th president of the College of Wooster on December 8, 2022.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The College of Wooster Libraries consists of three branches (Andrews Library, Flo K.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Gault Library, and Timken Science Library) and a music library located at the Scheide Music Center.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Andrews Library, the largest library in the system, houses more than 850,000 volumes and can accommodate over 500 readers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Andrews Library houses the college's Special Collections, media library and the student writing center.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The Timken Science Library in Frick Hall, the oldest branch in the system, served as the original academic library for the college from 1900 to 1962.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] After three decades as an art museum, the building reopened as the science library in 1998.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The College of Wooster Art Museum was established in the 1930s.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The current museum was established at the Ebert Art Center in 1997.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The museum houses two small galleries, the Charlene Derge Sussel Art Gallery and the Burton D.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Morgan Gallery, as well as storage for the college's permanent art collection.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The museum's encyclopedic collection spans from ancient to contemporary art.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Permanent collections include the John Taylor Arms Print Collection—which represents works by Edward Hopper, Winslow Homer, Isabel Bishop, Martin Lewis, James Abbott McNeill Whistler, Albrecht Dürer, Käthe Kollwitz and Félix Bracquemond—the William C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Mithoefer Collection of African Art, Middle Eastern pottery and Chinese decorative art.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The College of Wooster is a residential campus and has 16 residence halls, which house 16 to 270 students each, and 30 program houses.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] 97% of the student body live in the residence halls on campus.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The residence halls include Andrews Hall, Armington Hall, Babcock Hall, Bissman Hall, Bornhuetter Hall, Brush Hall, Compton Hall, Douglass Hall, Gault Manor, Gault Schoolhouse, Holden Hall, Kenarden Lodge, Luce Hall, Stevenson Hall, and Wagner Hall.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Elias Compton, former dean of the college, founded the Wooster in India program during the 1930s, which established a sister school relationship with Ewing Christian College in Allahabad, India.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Over a forty-year time span, Wooster sent several former students to serve as Head Resident at Ewing while Ewing faculty were brought to Wooster as Ewing Fellows; a plaque with the names of Ewing Fellows hangs in Babcock Hall.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The Wooster in India program helped build this unique bond between Wooster and India that enhanced the exchange of students, ideas and cultures.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] This international presence affected the entire campus, establishing a tradition which continues to influence the college.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Today, 15% of the student body is international in origin, representing 59 countries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college offers majors in Cultural Area Studies and International Relations, instruction in seven foreign languages and opportunities to study abroad in 60 countries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Sixty-nine percent of Wooster students are from outside of Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster is the home of the Ohio Light Opera, an enterprise founded within the college in 1979, but not part of the college curriculum.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] It is the only professional company in the United States entirely devoted to operetta.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] OLO performs the entire Gilbert & Sullivan repertoire, but also regularly revives rarely performed continental works of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Over the years, the company has produced eighty different operettas.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster's performing ensembles include the Wooster Symphony Orchestra, founded in 1915 by Daniel Parmelee, then Professor of Violin at the college.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The orchestra currently is the second-oldest orchestra in continuous performance in the state of Ohio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Additional ensembles include the Scot Symphonic and Marching Bands, the Wooster Chorus, and the Wooster Jazz Ensemble.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster has an active on-campus pipe band.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Officially called the College of Wooster Pipe Band, members perform at many official on-campus events such as commencement, sports games (football, basketball, swim meets, and sometimes lacrosse games) and many spontaneous student-run events.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] During the spring season, they perform and compete at a grade 3 level, having won prizes at the Scots wi' Shotts event in Cleveland hosted by the local Lochaber Pipe Band.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The Pipe Band also placed first in the grade 3 contest at the 2009 Toronto Indoor Highland Games, as the only American band competing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college's department of Theatre and Dance produces two dance concerts per year, a fall concert in the round, and a spring concert in a more formal proscenium setting.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Additionally, the college produces at least two plays each academic year.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Further plays are produced by student groups and seniors pursuing their Independent Study projects.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] In 2007, Wooster's theatre production of 'Nocturne' was invited to perform at the Kennedy Center's American College Theatre Festival in Washington, D.C.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster's production was one of four shows chosen from a field of approximately 400 entries.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The College of Wooster has hosted numerous fraternities, sororities and honor societies since its establishment.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] These number more than 80 Greek named chapters, including defunct groups, with approximately 30 active today.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The most visible are the college's Greek Academic and Social chapters.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] However, the Greek System includes Honor Societies and Professional Fraternities, along with Greek-aligned clubs and sections which adopted those terms when the words "fraternity" and "sorority" were discouraged.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] There are currently twelve active academic and social Greek groups at the College of Wooster: six sororities, five fraternities and one co-educational group.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Sometimes called clubs and sections, these groups are not affiliated with national Greek organizations, and approximately 15% of the student body participates.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster's twelve Greek chapters are self-governed under an Inter-Greek Council.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] At least eighteen honor societies are active at the college, including ΦΒΚ – Phi Beta Kappa, which arrived in 1926.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college has a wide variety of student-run media.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] *The Wooster Voice* is the weekly student newspaper with a newly launched website, and has been published weekly since 1883 (see list of college newspapers), while WOO 91, which was at WCWS-FM until 2019, is the college's online radio station that streams from iHeartRadio.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college also has a successful Ultimate Frisbee program.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The Women's team, Betty Gone Wild, won USAUltimate's D-III College Championship Sectionals in 2014 and 2015.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Also in 2014 and 2015, they came in second at USAUltimate's D-III College Championship Regionals.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] They attended the National College Championship in 2014 and came in 15th place.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The college is well known for its Moot Court team as part of the American Moot Court Association, ranked second in the nation in 2017 by the ACMA.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] In addition to the teams regional championships, the college routinely qualifies teams to the Moot Court Nationals tournament and was the 2008 National Champion.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] In 2017, Wooster qualified five teams to the nationals tournament and had teams finish 12th, 16th, and 18th in oral argument, 13th and 14th in oration, and third in appellate brief writing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster teams are named the *Fighting Scots*.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Wooster's athletic history dates back to its first baseball team, in 1880, which played only one game, losing 12–2 to Kenyon College.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] The football program was established in 1889; over its first two seasons, the team won all seven games it played, by a total score of 306–4.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Included was a 64–0 victory at Ohio State on November 1, 1890, in the Buckeyes' first-ever home football game.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Shortly thereafter, intercollegiate sports were banned by the College President.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] Sports sponsored include baseball, basketball, cross country, field hockey, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, softball, swimming, tennis, track and field, and volleyball.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/college-of-wooster] They compete in the North Coast Athletic Conference of NCAA Division III.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The specific editorial methodologies for various types of documents are developed and defined by archival science and other auxiliary sciences of history.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The term *documentary editing* is often confused with the editing of documentary films.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Mary-Jo Kline, the author of a key introductory book on the subject, remarked that she once found her treatise in the "movies and film" section of the bookstore.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editing grew out of the related field of scholarly editing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editors support historic scholarship by editing archival primary sources, whereas scholarly editors can support a broader range of disciplines using a wider variety of sources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Some editing projects overlap both terms, especially those related to literary analysis, which can involve both genetic editing of a literary work, and the documentary editing of associated primary sources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editing began out of a desire for historians to provide a foundation for future scholars.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The field grew in the late 1800s, with much of the work motivated by a desire to promote pride in local and national history.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] By the 1930s, documentary editing emerged as a specialization of professional archivists.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] By the late 1970s, documentary editing began using digital automation, and by the early 2000s, electronic publication was preferred over printed volumes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editing projects can be classified by the theme of the documents published.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editors are forced to be selective when choosing which archival documents to edit and publish.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Although the selection process is key to appraising the evidentiary value of the published documents, later scholars often lack the means to assess the original editor's selection decisions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Editors must also abide by any terms imposed by the custodian of the records.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] If the records are held in private collections, editors may persuade the owners to allow publication by noting that the originals of source documents can fetch higher prices at rare book auctions, a phenomenon termed "imprimatur value" by Katharine Leab.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Annotation helps readers understand the context of the published documents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Typographic errors may be annotated *sic*, or may be silently emended without annotation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Older texts may reflect historic orthography, requiring so much annotation that some editors omit *sic* to avoid distracting readers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] *Sic* may also be omitted when the error is *passim*, even in more modern documents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] For example, a publication of Irish diplomatic documents chose to not insert *sic* at each misusage of "England" as "Britain", choosing instead to explain the convention in their introduction.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Excessive annotations can cause a documentary publication to be regarded as secondary source, instead of as a compilation of primary sources.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Editors try to strike a balance between "letting the documents tell the story" and providing sufficient context to readers who may lack the editor's subject matter expertise.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editors historically published printed volumes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Printed volumes may contain transcribed documents, necessitating "a fair amount of hack work" to copy the text.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The texts of documents may be published in full, or be summarized to retain all important content, but to exclude more trivial and incidental matter.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] An abstracted text of this type is known in British English as a "calendar", although in American English that term is more typically applied to a more basic inventory of documents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] An alternative form of publication is photographic facsimiles.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Facsimile editions are traditionally more costly, but allow a closer fidelity to the original documents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Printed books, although less convenient than electronic editions, may help increase an editing project's accessibility and alleviate concerns about digital obsolescence.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Microform publication reduces costs, while allowing editors to avoid rote transcription.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Microform editions typically have minimal, if any annotation.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Microform publication is only suitable for legible documents, and works poorly on handwritten documents.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Microform editions are usually accompanied by a printed index, which many libraries store separately from the microform, potentially frustrating researchers.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Compared with printed editions, microform editions are less selective, and the large number of published documents can make it difficult for readers to find germane content.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Electronic publication allows documentary editors the fidelity of facsimiles, but without the added printing cost.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Further, as the archivist David Ferriero observed, electronic publication relieves library access services of the burden of reshelving heavy volumes.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The transition to electronic publication began when the United States National Archives commissioned a study on digital preservation in 1984.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The report, which was delivered in 1991, focused on the potential for publication via digital optical media, such as CD-ROM.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] The technical standards recommended in the report were used in early electronic documentary editing projects.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] As of the early 2010s, TEI format is preferred for electronic publication because of its extensibility and interoperability with other publishing tools.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editing is foundational to modern historic scholarship.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Primary sources are, after an editing project, both accessible and understandable to broader audience.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] A publication can serve to illustrate an historic field, drawing interest to a topic.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Documentary editing also serves a pedagogical function.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Document-based questions, common in secondary school history classes, draw upon edited documents to measure student skills at historic analysis.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/documentary-editing] Editing may also offer undergraduates an opportunity at historic research.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Environmentalism advocates the preservation, restoration and improvement of the natural environment and critical earth system elements or processes such as the climate, and may be referred to as a movement to control pollution or protect plant and animal diversity.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] For this reason, concepts such as a land ethics, environmental ethics, biodiversity, ecology, and the biophilia hypothesis figure predominantly.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The environmentalist movement encompasses various approaches to addressing environmental issues, including free market environmentalism, evangelical environmentalism, and the environmental conservation movement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] At its crux, environmentalism is an attempt to balance relations between humans and the various natural systems on which they depend in such a way that all the components are accorded a proper degree of sustainability.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The exact measures and outcomes of this balance is controversial and there are many different ways for environmental concerns to be expressed in practice.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Environmentalism and environmental concerns are often represented by the colour green, but this association has been appropriated by the marketing industries for the tactic known as greenwashing.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Environmentalism is opposed by anti-environmentalism, which says that the Earth is less fragile than some environmentalists maintain, and portrays environmentalism as overreacting to the human contribution to climate change or opposing human advancement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] An *environmentalist* is a person who may speak out about our natural environment and the sustainable management of its resources through changes in public policy or individual behaviour.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In various ways (for example, grassroots activism and protests), environmentalists and environmental organizations seek to give the natural world a stronger voice in human affairs.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In general terms, environmentalists advocate the sustainable management of resources, and the protection (and restoration, when necessary) of the natural environment through changes in public policy and individual behaviour.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In its recognition of humanity as a participant in ecosystems, the movement is centered around ecology, health, and human rights.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The *environmental movement* (a term that sometimes includes the conservation and green movements) is a diverse scientific, social, and political movement.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Though the movement is represented by a range of organizations, because of the inclusion of environmentalism in the classroom curriculum, the environmental movement has a younger demographic than is common in other social movements (see green seniors).
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] A concern for environmental protection has recurred in diverse forms, in different parts of the world, throughout history.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The earliest ideas of environmental protectionism can be found in Jainism, a religion from ancient India revived by Mahavira in the 6th century BC.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Jainism offers a view that is in many ways compatible with core values associated with environmental activism, such as the protection of life by nonviolence, which could form a strong ecological ethos for global protection of the environment.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Mahavira's teachings on the symbiosis between all living beings—as well as the five elements of earth, water, air, fire, and space—are core to environmental thought today.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The authors of such treatises included Al-Kindi, Qusta ibn Luqa, Al-Razi, Ibn Al-Jazzar, al-Tamimi, al-Masihi, Avicenna, Ali ibn Ridwan, Ibn Jumay, Isaac Israeli ben Solomon, Abd-el-latif, Ibn al-Quff, and Ibn al-Nafis.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Their works covered a number of subjects related to pollution, such as air pollution, water pollution, soil contamination, and the mishandling of municipal solid waste.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] They also included assessments of certain localities' environmental impact.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Within the religious tradition of the Catholic church, the friar Francis of Assisi gave expression to a profound mystical reverence for the natural environment as early as 1224.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In his lyrical poem *Canticle of the Sun* Francis offered both an ethical and spiritual context for the practice of environmentalism.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In Europe, King Edward I of England banned the burning and sale of "sea-coal" in 1272 by proclamation in London, after its smoke had become a prevalent annoyance throughout the city.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] This fuel, common in London due to the local scarcity of wood, was given this early name because it could be found washed up on some shores, from where it was carted away on a wheelbarrow.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] King Philip II of Spain was noted by his love of nature, which according to historian Henry Kamen, turned him into one of the first ecologist rulers in European history.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] He issued orders to conserve the Spanish forests, noting in 1582 the great disservice they would do to future generations by depleting them.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The origins of the environmental movement lay in the response to increasing levels of smoke pollution in the atmosphere during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The emergence of great factories and the concomitant immense growth in coal consumption gave rise to an unprecedented level of air pollution in industrial centers; after 1900 the large volume of industrial chemical discharges added to the growing load of untreated human waste.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The first large-scale, modern environmental laws came in the form of Britain's Alkali Acts, passed in 1863, to regulate the deleterious air pollution (gaseous hydrochloric acid) given off by the Leblanc process, used to produce soda ash.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] In industrial cities, local experts and reformers, especially after 1890, took the lead in identifying environmental degradation and pollution, and initiating grass-roots movements to demand and achieve reforms.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Typically the highest priority went to water and air pollution.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The late 19th century saw the passage of the first wildlife conservation laws.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The zoologist Alfred Newton published a series of investigations into the *Desirability of establishing a 'Close-time' for the preservation of indigenous animals* between 1872 and 1903.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] His advocacy for legislation to protect animals from hunting during the mating season led to the formation of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds and influenced the passage of the Sea Birds Preservation Act in 1869 as the first nature protection law in the world.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] The movement in the United States began in the late 19th century, out of concerns for protecting the natural resources of the West, with individuals such as John Muir and Henry David Thoreau making key philosophical contributions.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Thoreau was interested in peoples' relationship with nature and studied this by living close to nature in a simple life.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] He published his experiences in the book *Walden*, which argues that people should become intimately close with nature.
[src:kathleen-dean-moore/environmentalism] Muir came to believe in nature's inherent right, especially after spending time hiking in Yosemite Valley and studying both the ecology and geology.
